)|Will]]''\n|Sister Carmel\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Jail Caesar]]''\n|Pirate Captain\n|Also producer\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Thor: The Dark World]]''\n|[[Eir]]\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''The Little Vampire 3D''\n|Freda Sackville-Bagg \n|Voice\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[A Christmas Prince]]''\n|Queen Helena\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[A Christmas Prince: The Royal Wedding]]''\n|Queen Helena\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''A Rose in Winter''\n|Anna Reinach\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[A Christmas Prince: The Royal Baby]]''\n|Queen Helena\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Gretel & Hansel]]''\n|Holda\n| \n|-\n|Unknown \n|''Shingetsu''\n|Woman\n|Also producer\n|-\n|Unknown \n|''Echoes from the Past''\n|Andrea Foss\n|Post-production\n|-\n|Unknown \n|''[[The Bay of Silence]]''\n|Vivian\n|Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Play for Today|BBC2 Playhouse]]''\n|Emily\n|Episode: \"The Happy Autumn Fields\"\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[A Tale of Two Cities]]''\n|[[Lucie Manette]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]''\n|Diana Molner\n|Episode: \"Operation Susie\"\n|-\n|1983\n|''Arms and the Man''\n|Raina\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Ellis Island (miniseries)|Ellis Island]]''\n|Bridget O'Donnell\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Wallenberg: A Hero's Story]]''\n|Baroness Lisl Kemeny\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''\n|Nita Cochran\n|Episode: \"Murder in the Afternoon\"\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Dream West]]''\n|Jessie Benton Fremont\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Second Serve]]''\n|Gwen\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Baja Oklahoma]]''\n|[[Patsy Cline]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Max and Helen]]''\n|Helen Weiss\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1991\n|''Strauss Dynasty''\n|Olga\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[The Hidden Room (1991\u20131993 anthology TV series)|The Hidden Room]]''\n|Jennifer\n|Episode: \"Dream Child\"\n|-\n|1991\n|''L'Am\u00e9rique en otage''\n|Parveneh Limbert\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1992\n|''Ladykiller''\n|May Packard\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]''\n|Anne Berrisford\n|Episode: \"Wild Horses\"\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Judgment Day: The John List Story]]''\n|Jean Syfert\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1993\n|''Double Deception''\n|Pamela Sparrow\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Jack Reed: Badge of Honor]]''\n|Joan Anatole\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Scarlet and Black (TV series)|Scarlet and Black]]''\n|Madame de Renal\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Sharpe's Honour (TV programme)|Sharpe's Honour]]''\n|La Marquesa\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Joseph (1995 film)|Joseph]]''\n|[[Rachel]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Donor Unknown]]''\n|Alice Stillman\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Devil's Advocate (TV series)|Devil's Advocate]]''\n|Alessandra Locatelli\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Hidden in America]]''\n|Dee\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1997\n|''Indefensible: The Truth About Edward Brannigan''\n|Rebecca Daly\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Close Relations]]''\n|Louise\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Welcome to Paradox]]''\n|Aura Mendoza\n|Episode: \"Acute Triangle\"\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Deep in My Heart (1999 film)|Deep in My Heart]]''\n|Annalise Jurgenson\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Becker (TV series)|Becker]]''\n|Dr. Sandra Rush\n|Episode: \"Activate Your Choices\"\n|-\n|1999\n|''In the Company of Spies''\n|Sarah Gold\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Attila (miniseries)|Attila]]''\n|[[Galla Placidia]]\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]''\n|[[Borg (Star Trek)#Borg Queen|Borg Queen]]\n|Episode: \"[[Endgame (Star Trek: Voyager)|Endgame]]\"\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]''\n|Alma\n|Episodes: \"Out, Out, Brief Candle\" and \"The Plan\"\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Dinotopia (miniseries)|Dinotopia]]''\n|Rosemary Waldo\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Frank Herbert's Children of Dune|Children of Dune]]''\n|[[Lady Jessica]]\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|2003\n|''The Death and Life of Nancy Eaton''\n|Snubby Eaton\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[The Mystery of Natalie Wood]]''\n|Maria Gurdin\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2003, 2004\n|''[[Threat Matrix]]''\n|Senator Lily Randolph\n|Episodes: \"Flipping\" and \"19 Seconds\"\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Dynasty: The Making of a Guilty Pleasure]]''\n|[[Joan Collins]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]]''\n|Maddie\n|5 episodes\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]''\n|Gillian Booth\n|Episode: \"Dramma Giocoso\"\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[The Line of Beauty (TV series)|The Line of Beauty]]''\n|Rachel Fedden\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[The 4400]]''\n|Sarah\n|Episodes: \"Gone: Part 1\" and \"Gone: Part 2\"\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Persuasion (2007 film)|Persuasion]]''\n|[[Rachel Russell, Lady Russell|Lady Russell]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Heroes and Villains (TV series)|Heroes and Villains]]''\n|Letizia\n|Episode: \"Napoleon\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Dirty Sexy Money]]''\n|Judge Alexis Wyeth\n|Episode: \"The Family Lawyer\"\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Midsomer Murders]]''\n|Jenny Frazer\n|Episode: \"Secrets and Spies\"\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Waking the Dead (TV series)|Waking the Dead]]''\n|Karen Harding\n|Episodes: \"Care: Part 1\" and \"Care: Part 2\"\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Page Eight]]''\n|[[Emma Baron]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]''\n|Elena Gavrik\n|6 episodes\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Tyrant (TV series)|Tyrant]]''\n|Amira Al Fayeed\n|20 episodes\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]''\n|Margaret Clark\n|Episode: \"So It Goes\"\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[The Syndicate]]''\n|Lady Hazelwood\n|6 episodes\n|-\n|2015\n| ''[[Partners in Crime (UK TV series)|Partners in Crime]]''\n|Rita Vandemeyer\n|Episodes: \"The Secret Adversary: Part 1\" and \"The Secret Adversary: Part 2\"\n|-\n|2016/2019\n| ''[[The OA]]''\n|Nancy Johnson\n|Season 1 (2016): 8 episodes<br />Season 2 (2019): Episode: \"Angel of Death\"\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Carnival Row]]''\n| Aoife Tsigani\n| Recurring role<ref name=\"KrigeHarris\">{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title=\u2018Carnival Row\u2019: Alice Krige & Jared Harris Set To Recur On Amazon\u2019s Fantasy Drama Series|url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/carnival-row-alice-krige-jared-harris-recur-amazons-fantasy-drama-series-1202186955/|website=Deadline|accessdate=15 December 2017|date=12 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Alice Krige}}\n* {{IMDb name|481}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Amg name|39389}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060806045921/http://sci-fi-online.50megs.com/2006_Interviews/06-06-30_AliceKrige.htm Alice Krige interview] at [http://sci-fi-online.com www.sci-fi-online.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120119042017/http://www.whoswhosa.co.za/alice-krige-6346 Alice Krige] at [https://web.archive.org/web/20110901215042/http://www.whoswhosa.co.za/ Who's Who Southern Africa]\n\n{{Laurence Olivier Award for Best Newcomer in a Play}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krige, Alice}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Central School of Speech and Drama]]\n[[Category:Royal Shakespeare Company members]]\n[[Category:South African film actresses]]\n[[Category:South African film producers]]\n[[Category:South African television actresses]]\n[[Category:South African expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Upington]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:South African people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Shakespearean actresses]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:Rhodes University alumni]]\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use South African English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n | image          = Alice Krige 2006.jpg\n | image_size     = \n | caption        = Krige in October 2006\n | birth_name     = Alice Maud Krige\n | birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1954|6|28}}\n | birth_place    = [[Upington]], [[Northern Cape]], [[South Africa|South Africa]]\n | occupation     = Actress, producer\n | years_active   = 1976\u2013present\n | spouse         = {{marriage|Paul Schoolman|1988}}\n}}\n\n'''Alice Maud Krige''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|r|i\u02d0|\u0261|\u0259}}; born 28 June 1954) is a South African actress and producer. Her first feature film role was in ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' (1981) as the [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] singer [[Sybil Gordon]]. She is well known for playing the dual role of Eva Galli/Alma Mobley in ''[[Ghost Story (1981 film)|Ghost Story]]'', and the [[Borg (Star Trek)#Borg Queen|Borg Queen]] in the ''[[Star Trek]]'' franchise, beginning with the film ''[[Star Trek: First Contact]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.startrek.com/article/first-contacts-borg-queen-alice-krige|title=First Contact's Borg Queen - Alice Krige|work=StarTrek.com|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKrige was born in [[Upington]], [[Northern Cape Province]], South Africa, the daughter of Patricia, a professor of [[Psychology]], and Louis Krige, a physician. The Kriges later moved to [[Port Elizabeth]], where Alice grew up in what she has described as a \"very happy family\", with two brothers, one of whom became a physician and the other a Professor of Surgery.<ref name=bio>[https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800032063/bio Alice Krige biodata], Yahoo! Movies; accessed 29 September 2014.</ref><ref name=\"krige-bio\">[http://www.krige-page.com/biography.html The Alice Krige Home Page biography] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713170814/http://www.krige-page.com/biography.html |date=13 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nKrige attended [[Rhodes University]] in [[Grahamstown, South Africa]] with plans to become a [[clinical psychology|clinical psychologist]]. She turned to acting after taking an acting class at Rhodes, then completed a Bachelor of Arts degree and an BA Hons degree in drama, with distinction. She went on to London to attend the [[Central School of Speech and Drama]].<ref name=tribute>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribute.ca/people/alice-krige/5647|title=Alice Krige biography and filmography|publisher=Tribute.ca|accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKrige made her professional debut on British television in 1979, and appeared as Lucie Manette in the television movie ''[[A Tale of Two Cities]]''. She went on to play [[Sybil Gordon]] in ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' and Eva Galli/Alma Mobley in ''[[Ghost Story (1981 film)|Ghost Story]]'', both in 1981. She earned a Plays and Players Award, as well as a [[Laurence Olivier Award]] for Most Promising Newcomer, after appearing in a 1981 West End theatre production of [[George Bernard Shaw]]'s ''[[Arms and the Man]]''.<ref name=\"krige-bio\"/><ref name=tribute/> \n\nShe then joined the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]], playing Cordelia in ''[[King Lear]]'' and in [[Edward Bond]]'s ''Lear'', Miranda in ''[[The Tempest (play)|The Tempest]]'', Bianca in The ''[[Taming of the Shrew]]'', and Roxanne in ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]''. She also appeared in plays such as [[Thomas Otway]]'s ''[[Venice Preserv'd]]'' at the [[Almeida Theatre]] in London and ''Toyer'' at the [[Arts Theatre]] in the [[West End of London|West End]].\n\nKrige played [[Bathsheba]] in ''[[King David (film)|King David]]'' (1985) and [[Mary Shelley]] in ''[[Haunted Summer]]'' (1988), and has appeared in such horror films as ''[[Ghost Story (1981 film)|Ghost Story]]'', ''[[Sleepwalkers (film)|Sleepwalkers]]'', ''[[Silent Hill (film)|Silent Hill]]'' and ''[[Gretel & Hansel]]''.\n\nIn ''[[Star Trek: First Contact]]'', Krige played the [[Borg (Star Trek)#Borg Queen|Borg Queen]], who attempts to assimilate Earth into the Borg collective. She won Best Supporting Actress at the 1997 [[Saturn Award]]s for that role.<ref name=\"krige-bio\"/> She returned to this character in the Star Trek game ''[[Star Trek: Armada II]]'' and in the ''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]'' series finale \"[[Endgame (Star Trek: Voyager)|Endgame]]\" in 2001. Her science fiction career has expanded into television, with prominent roles in miniseries adaptations of ''[[Dinotopia (miniseries)|Dinotopia]]'' and ''[[Frank Herbert's Children of Dune]]''. She worked with the Brothers Quay in \"The Institute Benjamenta, or This Dream That People Call Life\" and with Guy Maddin in \"Twilight of the Ice Nymphs\".\n[[File:2008 10 10 Alice Krige 01.jpg|thumb|Krige at a ''Star Trek'' event]]\n\nIn April 2004, Krige was awarded an honorary [[Doctor of Letters|Litt.D.]] degree from [[Rhodes University]].<ref name=\"krige-bio\"/>\n\nKrige starred in a number of made-for-television movies and miniseries. She appeared in the television movies ''[[Baja Oklahoma]]'' (1988) and ''Ladykiller'' (1992) and the miniseries ''[[Ellis Island]]'' (1984) and ''[[Scarlet and Black (TV series)|Scarlet and Black]]'' (1993). She played [[Natalie Wood]]'s mother in ''[[The Mystery of Natalie Wood]]'' (2004), and starred as [[Joan Collins]] in ''[[Dynasty: The Making of a Guilty Pleasure]]''.<ref name=\"NYT 2005-01\">{{cite web|url=http://tv.nytimes.com/2005/01/01/arts/television/01heff.html|title=''Dynasty: The Making of a Guilty Pleasure'': If You've Got It, Flaunt It: ABC Trumpets an 80's Hit |last=Heffernan|first=Virginia|date=1 January 2005|work=The New York Times |accessdate=26 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.der-denver-clan.de/de/dynasty_behind.207.html|title=''Dynasty: The Making of a Guilty Pleasure'': Credits|publisher=Der-denver-clan.de|accessdate=27 February 2009}}</ref> She had recurring roles on ''[[Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]]'', and guest starred on ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'', ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'', ''[[The 4400]]'' and ''[[Dirty Sexy Money]]''.\n\nIn 2008, she had a leading role as Sannie Laing, Sandra's mother, in ''[[Skin (2008 film)|Skin]]'', the biopic about [[Sandra Laing]]. The film explores the issues of the girl being classified as \"Coloured\" by the South African authorities during [[Apartheid]], although her parents were white. In 2011, Krige appeared in the BBC's final season of ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]'', playing Russian [[double agent]] Elena Gavrik.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultbox.co.uk/news/headlines/1794-star-trek-star-alice-krige-is-amazing-in-spooks-say-writers|title='Star Trek' star Alice Krige is 'amazing' in 'Spooks', say writers|publisher=Cultbox.co.uk|date=8 September 2011|accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref> Krige also featured in the final season of the BBC drama ''[[Waking the Dead (TV series)|Waking the Dead]]'', in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/alice-krige/credits/139049 |title=Alice Krige Credits|publisher=Tvguide.com|date=28 November 2012|accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref> In recent years, Krige appeared in films ''[[Solomon Kane (film)|Solomon Kane]]'', ''[[The Sorcerer's Apprentice (2010 film)|The Sorcerer's Apprentice]]'' and ''[[Thor: The Dark World]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a399100/thor-the-dark-world-casts-alice-krige.html|title='Thor: The Dark World' casts Alice Krige|publisher=Digital Spy|date=13 August 2012|accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref> She played the role of Amira in the first and second series of ''[[Tyrant (TV series)|Tyrant]]'' for F/X, and has recently worked for the BBC on the series ''[[The Syndicate]]'' and ''[[Partners in Crime (UK TV series)|Partners in Crime]]''. In 2016, she appeared on the [[Netflix]] mystery series ''[[The OA]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thewrap.com/brit-marling-netflix-the-oa-mystery-trailer-video/|title=Brit Marling\u2019s Netflix Series \u2018The OA\u2019 Promises Mystery in First Trailer (Video)|publisher=The Wrap|date=December 12, 2016|accessdate=December 12, 2016|first=Linda|last=Ge}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Alice produced the award-winning feature ''[[Jail Caesar]]'', an exploration of the little known adolescence of [[Julius Caesar]], filmed in three working prisons with several hundred serving prisoners and an assemble of actors including [[Derek Jacobi]] and [[John Kani]]. ''Jail Caesar'' was written and directed by Paul Schoolman.\n\nIn 2015, Krige received the Special Jury Award at the International Film Festival for Peace, Inspiration and Equality in Jakarta, along with [[Andy Garcia]] and [[Jimmy Carter]] for her performance in the film ''Shingetsu'', in which she plays a war-traumatised surgeon of Doctors Without Borders, opposite Gunter Singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://internationalfilmfestivals.org/IFFPIE/winners.htm|title=Winners - International Film Festivals for Peace, Inspiration, and Equality|website=internationalfilmfestivals.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hastingsonlinetimes.co.uk/arts-culture/shingetsu-director-paul-schoolman-and-actor-alice-krige-interview|title=Shingetsu director Paul Schoolman and actor Alice Krige interview|website=hastingsonlinetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKrige married writer and director Paul Schoolman in 1988.<ref name=\"krige-bio\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1976\n|''Vergeet My Nie''\n|Welma de Villiers\n|\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Chariots of Fire]]''\n|[[Sybil Gordon]]\n|\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Ghost Story (1981 film)|Ghost Story]]''\n|Eva Galli / Alma Mobley\n|\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[King David (film)|King David]]''\n|[[Bathsheba]]\n|\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Barfly (film)|Barfly]]''\n|Tully Sorenson\n|\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Haunted Summer]]''\n|[[Mary Shelley|Mary Wollstonecraft Godwin]]\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[See You in the Morning (film)|See You in the Morning]]''\n|Beth Goodwin\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Sleepwalkers (film)|Sleepwalkers]]''\n|Mary Brady\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''Spies Inc.''\n|Isabelle\n|\n|-\n|1994\n|''Sea Beggars''\n|Wife\n|Short film\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Institute Benjamenta]]''\n|Lisa Benjamenta\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Star Trek: First Contact]]''\n|[[Borg (Star Trek)#Borg Queen|Borg Queen]]\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''Amanda''\n|Audrey Farnsworth\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Habitat (film)|Habitat]]''\n|Clarissa Symes\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Twilight of the Ice Nymphs]]''\n|Zephyr Eccles\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[The Commissioner (film)|The Commissioner]]''\n|Isabelle Morton\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Molokai: The Story of Father Damien]]''\n|[[Mother Marianne Cope]]\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[The Little Vampire (film)|The Little Vampire]]''\n|Freda Sackville-Bagg\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[The Calling (2000 film)|The Calling]]''\n|Elizabeth Plummer\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''Superstition''\n|Mirella Cenci\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''Vallen''\n|[[Monique]]\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Reign of Fire (film)|Reign of Fire]]''\n|Karen Abercromby\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Star Trek: The Experience|Star Trek: The Experience - Borg Invasion 4D]]''\n|Borg Queen\n|Short film\n|-\n|2004\n|''Shadow of Fear''\n|Margie Henderson\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Stay Alive]]''\n|The Author\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Silent Hill (film)|Silent Hill]]''\n|Christabella LaRoache\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Lonely Hearts (2006 film)|Lonely Hearts]]''\n|Janet Long\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[The Contract (2006 film)|The Contract]]''\n|Agent Gwen Miles\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Ten Inch Hero]]''\n|Zo\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Skin (2008 film)|Skin]]''\n|Sannie Laing\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[The Betrayed (2008 film)|The Betrayed]]''\n|Falco\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Solomon Kane (film)|Solomon Kane]]''\n|Katherine Crowthorn\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[The Sorcerer's Apprentice (2010 film)|The Sorcerer's Apprentice]]''\n|[[Morgan le Fay]]\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Will (2011 film)|Will]]''\n|Sister Carmel\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Jail Caesar]]''\n|Pirate Captain\n|Also producer\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Thor: The Dark World]]''\n|[[Eir]]\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''The Little Vampire 3D''\n|Freda Sackville-Bagg \n|Voice\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[A Christmas Prince]]''\n|Queen Helena\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[A Christmas Prince: The Royal Wedding]]''\n|Queen Helena\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''A Rose in Winter''\n|Anna Reinach\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[A Christmas Prince: The Royal Baby]]''\n|Queen Helena\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Gretel & Hansel]]''\n|Holda\n| \n|-\n|Unknown \n|''Shingetsu''\n|Woman\n|Also producer\n|-\n|Unknown \n|''Echoes from the Past''\n|Andrea Foss\n|Post-production\n|-\n|Unknown \n|''[[The Bay of Silence]]''\n|Vivian\n|Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Play for Today|BBC2 Playhouse]]''\n|Emily\n|Episode: \"The Happy Autumn Fields\"\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[A Tale of Two Cities]]''\n|[[Lucie Manette]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]''\n|Diana Molner\n|Episode: \"Operation Susie\"\n|-\n|1983\n|''Arms and the Man''\n|Raina\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Ellis Island (miniseries)|Ellis Island]]''\n|Bridget O'Donnell\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Wallenberg: A Hero's Story]]''\n|Baroness Lisl Kemeny\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''\n|Nita Cochran\n|Episode: \"Murder in the Afternoon\"\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Dream West]]''\n|Jessie Benton Fremont\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Second Serve]]''\n|Gwen\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Baja Oklahoma]]''\n|[[Patsy Cline]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Max and Helen]]''\n|Helen Weiss\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1991\n|''Strauss Dynasty''\n|Olga\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[The Hidden Room (1991-1993 anthology TV series)|The Hidden Room]]''\n|Jennifer\n|Episode: \"Dream Child\"\n|-\n|1991\n|''L'Am\u00e9rique en otage''\n|Parveneh Limbert\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1992\n|''Ladykiller''\n|May Packard\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]''\n|Anne Berrisford\n|Episode: \"Wild Horses\"\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Judgment Day: The John List Story]]''\n|Jean Syfert\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1993\n|''Double Deception''\n|Pamela Sparrow\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Jack Reed: Badge of Honor]]''\n|Joan Anatole\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Scarlet and Black (TV series)|Scarlet and Black]]''\n|Madame de Renal\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Sharpe's Honour (TV programme)|Sharpe's Honour]]''\n|La Marquesa\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Joseph (1995 film)|Joseph]]''\n|[[Rachel]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Donor Unknown]]''\n|Alice Stillman\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Devil's Advocate (TV series)|Devil's Advocate]]''\n|Alessandra Locatelli\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Hidden in America]]''\n|Dee\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1997\n|''Indefensible: The Truth About Edward Brannigan''\n|Rebecca Daly\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Close Relations]]''\n|Louise\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Welcome to Paradox]]''\n|Aura Mendoza\n|Episode: \"Acute Triangle\"\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Deep in My Heart (1999 film)|Deep in My Heart]]''\n|Annalise Jurgenson\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Becker (TV series)|Becker]]''\n|Dr. Sandra Rush\n|Episode: \"Activate Your Choices\"\n|-\n|1999\n|''In the Company of Spies''\n|Sarah Gold\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Attila (miniseries)|Attila]]''\n|[[Galla Placidia]]\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]''\n|[[Borg (Star Trek)#Borg Queen|Borg Queen]]\n|Episode: \"[[Endgame (Star Trek: Voyager)|Endgame]]\"\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]''\n|Alma\n|Episodes: \"Out, Out, Brief Candle\" and \"The Plan\"\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Dinotopia (miniseries)|Dinotopia]]''\n|Rosemary Waldo\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Frank Herbert's Children of Dune|Children of Dune]]''\n|[[Lady Jessica]]\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|2003\n|''The Death and Life of Nancy Eaton''\n|Snubby Eaton\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[The Mystery of Natalie Wood]]''\n|Maria Gurdin\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2003, 2004\n|''[[Threat Matrix]]''\n|Senator Lily Randolph\n|Episodes: \"Flipping\" and \"19 Seconds\"\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Dynasty: The Making of a Guilty Pleasure]]''\n|[[Joan Collins]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]]''\n|Maddie\n|5 episodes\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]''\n|Gillian Booth\n|Episode: \"Dramma Giocoso\"\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[The Line of Beauty (TV series)|The Line of Beauty]]''\n|Rachel Fedden\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[The 4400]]''\n|Sarah\n|Episodes: \"Gone: Part 1\" and \"Gone: Part 2\"\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Persuasion (2007 film)|Persuasion]]''\n|[[Rachel Russell, Lady Russell|Lady Russell]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Heroes and Villains (TV series)|Heroes and Villains]]''\n|Letizia\n|Episode: \"Napoleon\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Dirty Sexy Money]]''\n|Judge Alexis Wyeth\n|Episode: \"The Family Lawyer\"\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Midsomer Murders]]''\n|Jenny Frazer\n|Episode: \"Secrets and Spies\"\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Waking the Dead (TV series)|Waking the Dead]]''\n|Karen Harding\n|Episodes: \"Care: Part 1\" and \"Care: Part 2\"\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Page Eight]]''\n|[[Emma Baron]]\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]''\n|Elena Gavrik\n|6 episodes\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Tyrant (TV series)|Tyrant]]''\n|Amira Al Fayeed\n|20 episodes\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]''\n|Margaret Clark\n|Episode: \"So It Goes\"\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[The Syndicate]]''\n|Lady Hazelwood\n|6 episodes\n|-\n|2015\n| ''[[Partners in Crime (UK TV series)|Partners in Crime]]''\n|Rita Vandemeyer\n|Episodes: \"The Secret Adversary: Part 1\" and \"The Secret Adversary: Part 2\"\n|-\n|2016/2019\n| ''[[The OA]]''\n|Nancy Johnson\n|Season 1 (2016): 8 episodes<br />Season 2 (2019): Episode: \"Angel of Death\"\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Carnival Row]]''\n| Aoife Tsigani\n| Recurring role<ref name=\"KrigeHarris\">{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title=\u2018Carnival Row\u2019: Alice Krige & Jared Harris Set To Recur On Amazon\u2019s Fantasy Drama Series|url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/carnival-row-alice-krige-jared-harris-recur-amazons-fantasy-drama-series-1202186955/|website=Deadline|accessdate=15 December 2017|date=12 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Alice Krige}}\n* {{IMDb name|481}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Amg name|39389}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060806045921/http://sci-fi-online.50megs.com/2006_Interviews/06-06-30_AliceKrige.htm Alice Krige interview] at [http://sci-fi-online.com www.sci-fi-online.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120119042017/http://www.whoswhosa.co.za/alice-krige-6346 Alice Krige] at [https://web.archive.org/web/20110901215042/http://www.whoswhosa.co.za/ Who's Who Southern Africa]\n\n{{Laurence Olivier Award for Best Newcomer in a Play}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krige, Alice}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Central School of Speech and Drama]]\n[[Category:Royal Shakespeare Company members]]\n[[Category:South African film actresses]]\n[[Category:South African film producers]]\n[[Category:South African television actresses]]\n[[Category:South African expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Upington]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:South African people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Shakespearean actresses]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:Rhodes University alumni]]\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Eric Pode lives", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision:en-dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_Krige"}
{"title_page": "Augustana (band)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Augustana\n| image = Augustana - Chicago 2010.jpg\n| caption = Augustana, Chicago 2010\n| landscape = Yes\n| background = group_or_band\n| alias =\n| origin = [[Santa Ana, California]], U.S.\n| genre = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[indie rock]], [[pop rock]]\n| years_active = 2003-2011, 2012-present\n| label = [[Epic Records|Epic]], [[Razor & Tie]], Washington Square\n| associated_acts = The Last Almanac, [[Bad Things (band)|Bad Things]], [[Counting Crows]]\n| website = {{URL|www.augustanamusic.com}}\n| current_members = [[Daniel Layus|Dan Layus]]\n| past_members = Jared Palomar <br />  Justin South <br />John Vincent<br /> Josiah Rosen<br /> Chris Sachtleben  \n}}\n\n'''Augustana''' is an American [[rock music|rock]] band from [[San Diego]], [[California]] that has released five albums and an EP while being signed to [[Epic Records]] and [[Razor & Tie]].<ref name=\"epic\">{{cite web|url = http://www.alternativeaddiction.com/musicnews/article/2404/Dan-Layus-on-Augustanas-Uncertain-Future|work = alternativeaddiction.com|title = Dan Layus on Augustana's Uncertain Future|date = January 16, 2012|last = Jones|first = Ryan|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120121090019/http://www.alternativeaddiction.com/musicnews/article/2404/Dan-Layus-on-Augustanas-Uncertain-Future|archivedate=January 21, 2012 }}</ref> They are best known for their song \"[[Boston (song)|Boston]]\" and the album ''All the Stars and Boulevards'', both entering the Billboard charts.<ref name=\":0\" /> They are fronted by [[Dan Layus]] who currently is the only remaining member of the band.\n\n==History==\n===Early career===\nIn Autumn 2002 at [[Greenville College]] in Illinois, Dan Layus brought friends Josiah Rosen, Kyle Baker, and Simeon Lohrmann together to write and create music. They began out by re-recording the song \"More than a Love Song\" which Dan had written for his high school girlfriend while living in California. They originally wanted to call themselves The Looking Glass, but after discovering another band of the same name they chose \"Augustana\" instead. A full-length debut album, ''Midwest Skies and Sleepless Mondays'' was recorded in the home recording studio of Jon King.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Augustana - Midwest Skies And Sleepless Mondays|url = http://www.discogs.com/Augustana-Midwest-Skies-And-Sleepless-Mondays/release/6223817|website = Discogs|accessdate = 2015-10-13}}</ref> The album was released in the Spring of 2003 and only 1000 copies were produced, however, early buzz and reviews were primarily positive. Later that year the band recorded and released 25 copies of the Mayfield EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dirtbagsdelight.wordpress.com/2008/02/12/interview-jared-palomar-of-augustana/ |title=Interview: Jared Palomar of Augustana \u00ab Dirtbag\u2019s Delight |publisher=Dirtbagsdelight.wordpress.com |date=2008-02-12 |accessdate=2011-07-19| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110718092715/http://dirtbagsdelight.wordpress.com/2008/02/12/interview-jared-palomar-of-augustana/| archivedate= 18 July 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nDan Layus decided to move back to Southern California with band mate Josiah Rosen, where they eventually found their drummer, Justin South.  The band joined numerous tours with artists such as [[Switchfoot]], [[Maroon 5]], [[The Fray (band)|The Fray]], [[Counting Crows]], [[Dashboard Confessional]], [[O.A.R. (band)|O.A.R.]], [[Snow Patrol]], [[The Damnwells]], [[Goo Goo Dolls]], [[Acceptance (band)|Acceptance]], [[Cartel (band)|Cartel]], and [[OneRepublic]], as well as having their own headlining tours.\n\n===''All the Stars and Boulevards'' (2005-2007)===\n''[[All the Stars and Boulevards]]'' was released September 6, 2005<ref>{{Cite web|title = Augustana - All The Stars And Boulevards|url = http://www.discogs.com/Augustana-All-The-Stars-And-Boulevards/release/1744234|website = Discogs|accessdate = 2015-10-13}}</ref> and reached #1 on the Billboard [[Top Heatseekers]] chart and #96 on the [[Billboard Top 200]] chart.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Augustana - Chart history {{!}} Billboard|url = http://www.billboard.com/artist/280242/augustana/chart|website = www.billboard.com|accessdate = 2015-10-13}}</ref> The first single from the album, \"[[Boston (song)|Boston]]\", was released in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Augustana - Boston|url = http://www.discogs.com/Augustana-Boston/release/2704654|website = Discogs|accessdate = 2015-10-13}}</ref> This version differs from the one on their debut album, ''Midwest Skies and Sleepless Mondays''. The album was made available exclusively at [[Best Buy]] stores, and the [[Best Buy]] website, where it was sold out by the following day. The new features on this re-release are a re-mixed version of \"Wasteland\"; a new track named \"Marie\"; and acoustic versions and music videos of \"Boston\" and \"Stars and Boulevards\". Their most recognizable song is \"Boston\" which made it all the way to 34 on the Billboard top 100, as well as appearing on television shows ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'', ''[[Smallville]]'', [[Hidden Palms]], and ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]''. [[Leonard Hofstadter]] is heard singing it in the third episode of Season 1 of ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]''. Josiah Rosen left the band soon after. At the beginning of 2007, the band embarked on their second headlining tour, supported by [[Vega4]]. The band also opened for [[Chris Carrabba]] of [[Dashboard Confessional]] in late 2007.\n\n===''Can't Love, Can't Hurt'' (2008-2010)===\nThe band released their second album, ''[[Can't Love, Can't Hurt]]'', on April 29, 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Augustana - Can't Love, Can't Hurt|url = http://www.discogs.com/Augustana-Cant-Love-Cant-Hurt/release/2644706|website = Discogs|accessdate = 2015-10-13}}</ref> The first single from the album is titled \"[[Sweet and Low (Augustana song)|Sweet and Low]]\". The second single, \"I Still Ain't Over You\" reached #22 on the [[Adult album alternative]] chart. On May 1, 2008, the band appeared on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]''. Following personnel problems, the band had to cancel their European/North American tour for fall 2010.\n\n===''Augustana'' (2011-2013)===\nAugustana's [[Augustana (album)|self-titled, fourth full-length album]] was released on April 26, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Augustana - Augustana|url = http://www.discogs.com/Augustana-Augustana/release/4213777|website = Discogs|accessdate = 2015-10-13}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"Steal Your Heart\", was planned for a radio release on February 14 in order to coincide with [[Valentine's Day]], but was released early on the 8th of February on [[AOL Music]].<ref>[http://music.aol.com/blog/2011/02/08/augustana-steal-your-heart-song Augustana \"Steal Your Heart\" Song Exclusive] music.aol.com 2011-02-08 Retrieved 2011-02-12</ref>  Another song off the album \"Just Stay Here Tonight\" was used in an episode of ''[[Private Practice (TV series)|Private Practice]]''. \"Steal Your Heart\" was also used in the extended length Degrassi promo for the 11th season. They were featured on the Late Show with David Letterman and performed \"Steal Your Heart\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = Augustana Owns Its Sound on Self-Titled Third Album|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/472145/augustana-owns-its-sound-on-self-titled-third-album|website = Billboard|accessdate = 2015-10-13|date = April 8, 2011|first = Mike|last = Wood}}</ref>\n\nAugustana parted ways with Epic Records shortly after the album's release and on 11 November 2011, Dan Layus announced that all remaining members had amicably parted ways, but that he would continue to tour and perform under the name Augustana.<ref name=\"epic\" /> On 22 July 2013, Dan Layus announced that Augustana was signed to a new record deal.\n\n===''Life Imitating Life'' (2014-Present)===\nIn early 2014 the band announced that they had signed with Razor & Tie. On April 22, 2014, Augustana released the album, ''Life Imitating Life''.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Augustana - Life Imitating Life|url = http://www.discogs.com/Augustana-Life-Imitating-Life/release/6307738|website = Discogs|accessdate = 2015-10-13}}</ref> They also premiered the first single, \"Ash and Ember\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Premiere: Augustana's new single 'Ash and Ember'|url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/03/03/augustana-ash-and-ember-premiere/5924349/|website = usatoday.com|accessdate = 2015-10-13|date = March 3, 2014|last = Mansfield|first = Brian|publisher = USA Today}}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 2015, Augustana released three new tracks (\"Climb\", \"Must Be Love\" and \"You Can Have Mine\") on an EP titled \"Side A\".\n\nIn 2016, they began touring as an opener for the [[Dixie Chicks]] on their [[DCX MMXVI World Tour]].\n\nOn August 3, 2016, Augustana's social media sites changed their names to Dan Layus, the name of the sole remaining founding member and lead singer/songwriter.\n\nDan Layus released the album, ''Dangerous Things'', on October 21, 2016.\n\nOn August 28, 2019, as Augustana, the song \"For Now, Forever\" was released as a single with \"The Heart of It\" as its B-side.<ref>http://hard8workinggroup.com/augustana-new-music-for-now-forever-the-heart-of-it/</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n'''Last Line-up'''\n* Dan Layus <small>([[lead vocalist|vocals]], [[rhythm guitar|guitar]], [[piano]])</small>\n\n'''Former Members'''\n*Jared Palomar (bass guitar, vocals, keyboards)\n*Chris Sachtleben (lead guitar, vocals)\n*Justin South (drums)\n*Josiah Rosen (lead guitar, vocals)\n*John Vincent (piano, keyboards, vocals)\n*Josh Calhoun (drums)\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Album details\n!colspan=\"6\"| Peak\n!rowspan=\"2\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<br /><small>([[List of best selling music artists|sales threshold]])</small>\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n!width=\"40\"| [[Billboard Top 200|US]]\n!width=\"40\"| [[Top Digital Albums|US<br/>Digital]]\n!width=\"40\"| [[Top Heatseekers|US<br/>Heat]]\n!width=\"40\"| [[Top Independent Albums|US<br/>Indie]]\n!width=\"40\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]\n!width=\"40\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| 2005\n|align=\"left\"| ''[[All the Stars and Boulevards]]''\n* Label: Epic Records\n* Format: [[Compact disc|CD]]\n| 96\n| 107\n| 1\n| 1\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|align=\"left\"| \n*US: 345,000<ref name=\":1\" />\n*WW: 1,900,000\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| 2008\n|align=\"left\"| ''[[Can't Love, Can't Hurt]]''\n* Label: Epic\n* Format: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Digital data|Digital]], [[Vinyl record|Vinyl]]\n| 21\n| 77\n| \u2014\n| 2\n| 45\n| 114\n|align=\"left\"| \n*US: 121,000<ref name=\":1\" />\n*WW: 200,000\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| 2011\n|align=\"left\"| ''[[Augustana (album)|Augustana]]''\n* Label: Epic\n* Format: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Digital data|Digital]]\n| 29\n| 12\n| \u2014\n| 1\n| \u2014\n| 113\n|align=\"left\"| \n*US: 12,546\n*WW: 27,000\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| 2014\n|align=\"left\"| ''[[Life Imitating Life]]''\n* Label: Washington Square\n* Format: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Digital data|Digital]]\n| 67\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|align=\"left\"| \n|-\n\n|colspan=\"10\" style=\"font-size:8pt\"| \"\u2014\" denotes releases that did not chart\n|}\n\n===Independent albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Album details\n!colspan=\"6\"| Peak\n!rowspan=\"2\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<br /><small>([[List of best selling music artists|sales threshold]])</small>\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n!width=\"40\"| [[Billboard Top 200|US]]\n!width=\"40\"| [[Top Digital Albums|US<br/>Digital]]\n!width=\"40\"| [[Top Heatseekers|US<br/>Heat]]\n!width=\"40\"|