[Image:Atlantic Beach and Long Beach Aeriel View.JPG|thumb|300px|panorama|Aerial view; the left half is Atlantic Beach]]\n[[File:Atlantic-beach-ny-map.gif|thumb|U.S. Census Map]]\n\n'''Atlantic Beach''' is a [[Administrative divisions of New York#Village|village]] in New York and one of the wealthiest beach towns in America. It is located off the [[South Shore (Long Island)|South Shore]] of [[Long Island]] in the [[Hempstead (town), New York|Town of Hempstead]], [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://247wallst.com/special-report/2019/07/22/americas-richest-beach-towns|title=America\u2019s 34 richest beach towns|last=Stockdale|first=Charles|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://247wallst.com/special-report/2019/07/22/americas-richest-beach-towns/5/|title=America\u2019s Richest Beach Towns \u2013 Page 5 \u2013 24/7 Wall St.|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> It is located on [[Long Beach Barrier Island]], one of the [[Outer barrier|outer barrier islands]] which it shares with [[Long Beach, New York|Long Beach]], [[East Atlantic Beach, New York|East Atlantic Beach]], [[Lido Beach, New York|Lido Beach]] and [[Point Lookout, New York|Point Lookout]]. To the North, Atlantic Beach is bordered by [[Reynolds Channel|Reynold's Channel]] and [[East Rockaway Inlet]]. Atlantic Beach is home to the oldest beach club in the United States, the Lawrence Beach Club. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oceanclubli.com/dsp_history.cfm|title=The Ocean Club - History|website=oceanclubli.com|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The village is a \"high-class private setting exclusively for the rich with many mansions and summer homes priced in the millions\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.longislandexchange.com/towns/atlantic-beach/|title=Atlantic Beach|website=www.longislandexchange.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>.\n\n[[File:Atlantic Beach New York jetty with US flag.jpg|thumb|Jetty extending into the Atlantic Ocean]]\n \nAs of the [[2010 United States Census]], the village population was 1,891.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov |title=Race, Hispanic or Latino, Age, and Housing Occupancy: 2010 Census Redistricting Data (Public Law 94-171) Summary File (QT-PL), Atlantic Beach village, New York |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=September 30, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the summer months, the population swells by thousands as people flood the beaches<ref>Cotsalas, Valerie. [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/08/realestate/08lizo.html?ex=1181793600&en=4c3e61cc1175c9e3&ei=5070 \"A Village Is Thinking Beyond Cabanas\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', April 8, 2007. Accessed June 12, 2007.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Berger|first=Joseph|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/11/nyregion/11ritual.html|title=At These Cabanas, \u2018The Tiles That Bind\u2019|date=2010-07-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Ingrassia|first=Michele|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/23/nyregion/a-summerful-of-labor-days.html|title=A Summerful of Labor Days|date=2006-07-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the summer residents move in.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Konrad|first=Walecia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/20/travel/havens-back-for-the-memories-at-atlantic-beach.html|title=HAVENS; Back for the Memories at Atlantic Beach|date=2003-06-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Atlantic Beach residents may obtain season passes and access the beaches through nine entrances.<ref>Konrad, Walecia. [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/20/travel/havens-back-for-the-memories-at-atlantic-beach.html \"HAVENS; Back for the Memories at Atlantic Beach\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 20, 2003. Accessed August 24, 2009.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/08/nyregion/a-beach-to-some-it-s-home-to-others.html|title=A Beach to Some, It's Home to Others|date=2001-07-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/classifieds/real-estate/island-park-home-sales-1.19357599|title=Everything 'walkable to the beach' in LI community|website=Newsday|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> It has been described as the \"Genuine 'Old New York' paradise\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/08/19/this-beach-club-is-the-genuine-old-new-york-paradise/|title=This beach club is the genuine \u2018old New York\u2019 paradise|last=Markowicz|first=Karol|date=2018-08-20|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural and literary references==\n\n===Film and literature===\n*In [[Mario Puzo]]'s [[The Godfather (novel)|1969 novel]] and its eponymous film adaptation, ''[[The Godfather]]'' (1972), Atlantic Beach is home to the character [[Sonny Corleone]]. (Sonny's father, Don [[Vito Corleone]], lives in neighboring [[Long Beach, New York|Long Beach]]).\n*[[Garry Marshall]]'s film ''[[The Flamingo Kid]]'' (1984) centers on a fictional beach club (based on the old El Patio beach club) set in Atlantic Beach. The film was shot on location at an actual beach club in [[Breezy Point, Queens|Breezy Point]] on the [[Rockaway, Queens|Rockaway Peninsula]].\n*A scene from [[Martin Scorsese]]'s film ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990) was shot at Catalina Beach Club.\n*Scenes from [[Ed Burns]]' film ''[[She's the One (1996 film)|She's the One]]'' (1996) were shot at Sun and Surf Beach Club.\n\n===Television===\n*Scenes from HBO's ''[[Boardwalk Empire]]'' were filmed in summer 2011.\n*Scenes from the NBC series, ''[[Law & Order]]'' were shot at the Sands Beach Club and the famous Atlantic Beach Surf Shop.\n*Scenes from [[USA Network]]'s series ''[[Royal Pains]]'' were taped at Catalina Beach Club.\n*Multiple scenes from the [[HBO]] series ''[[The Sopranos]]'' were shot in Atlantic Beach as wealthy mobster [[Little Carmine Lupertazzi]] lived here.<ref>{{cite web|website=IMDb|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0141842/locations|title= Filming Locations for \"The Sopranos\" |date=1999|accessdate= November 23, 2006}}</ref>\n*Scenes of [[The Blacklist (TV series)|Blacklist]] were shot at the Lawrence Beach Club in Atlantic Beach, (season 3, ep 19, Cape May)<ref>{{cite web|website=IMDb|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5182086/locations |title= Filming Locations for \"blacklist\" |date=2016|accessdate= November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n*Atlantic Beach was featured in [[HGTV|HGTV's]] [[House Hunters]], (season 169, ep 13, Beauty on the Beach or Castle in the Sky)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liherald.com/fivetowns/stories/north-woodmere-resident-gil-shemtov-to-highlight-atlantic-beach,114284|title=North Woodmere resident Gil Shemtov to highlight Atlantic Beach|website=Herald Community Newspapers|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Conception ===\nThe first real interest in the  barrier island of Atlantic Beach came in 1922 when [[Robert Moses]], the famous highway builder and public works czar, and Chairman of the [[New York State Council of Parks|State Council of Parks]], included Atlantic beach as part of his \"State Park Plan for New York\". The blueprint, which is on file at the archives in Albany, showed a parkway from central Queens to a bridge crossing [[Reynolds Channel]] with architecturally refined facilities for thousands of beach goers; unfortunately however, cost overruns on many of Mr. Moses' other projects at the time and other factors dampened his plans which were ultimately abandoned.\n<br />\n=== Founding and Early History ===\nIn 1923, the village\u2019s first developer, Atlantic Beach Associates led by Stephen P. Pettit(1880-1925), a former [[Nassau County Sheriff's Department (New York)|Nassau County Sheriff]] and banker from Freeport, N.Y., had dreams of creating a place that would rival the City of Long Beach, which was created by a Politician and amusement park operator named [[Long Beach, New York|William H. Reynolds]]. He died just after buying land for 3,500 lots in Atlantic Beach<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1925/09/10/104185710.html?pageNumber=25|title=STEPHEN P. PETTIT DEAD.,; Freeport Banker and 'Realty Operator Dies of Heart Disease.|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\n\n\nIn 1926, real estate tycoon William Austin (Official. William Austin Jr.), who graduated from [[Yale University]], with his associate, Charles N. Talbot Jr, formed Island Park Associates which purchased the land for $4,000,000<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ihfK-S-Iv2AC&pg=RA2-PA37&lpg=RA2-PA37&dq=Atlantic+beach+homes+built+in+1928&source=bl&ots=9oonKqnlRF&sig=ACfU3U32LkWRkKKLKiZz-kXIwKNRPQVesw&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjk67uY-NjoAhV2mXIEHcrzBNcQ6AEwBHoECAoQJw#v=onepage&q=Atlantic%20beach%20homes%20built%20in%201928&f=false|title=Supreme Court|language=en}}</ref>. William Austin was married to Actress Josephine Sanders, better known as [[Irene Delroy]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1937/07/02/94396396.html?pdf_redirect=true&site=false|title=IRENE DELROY GETS DECREE; Actress Obtains Divorce in Reno From William L. Austin Jr.|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>; the wedding was officiated by Mayor James J. Walker on July 15, 1931<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0217835/bio|title=Irene Delroy|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1937/05/21/94377804.html?pageNumber=19|title=IRENE DELROY IN RENO; She Plans Suit for Divorce From William L. Austin Jr.|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>[[1940 United States Census|.]] Austin and Talbot completed Pettit's preliminary dredging and. shoring work, and proceeded to subdivide the property. They installed gas and electricity lines, and a sanitary sewer system was installed in 1927. They began selling land and building homes; the first 45 of the 150 homes they planned on building were financed using a mortgage from The Title Guarantee and Trust Company. The. homes were all designed with seven rooms, two baths, private detached garages on 48' x 88' lots and were built in a wide array of styles.&nbsp;Mr. Austin finished Petitt\u2019s plan to build a [[Atlantic Beach Bridge|bridge]] between Far Rockaway and Atlantic beach, which was opened and dedicated on June 29, 1927. A boardwalk was planned for the entire ocean side but, as constructed, it was about a mile long, stretching from west of The Plaza and extending beyond Vernon Avenue, and double the width of the boardwalk which exists today. \n\n\nThe Castles Beach Club opened in May 1928, which contained one of the largest pools on the [[South Shore (Long Island)|South Shore of Long Island]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1927/06/26/issue.html|title=TimesMachine: Sunday June 26, 1927 - NYTimes.com|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>. The Atlantic Beach Club<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/08/18/93988729.html?pdf_redirect=true&site=false|title=Members of Club Participate In Gay Programs of Season; Tennis Tournaments, Style Shows, a Photography Contest and Barn Dance Are Scheduled|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>, later known as the Atlantic Beach Hotel and Cabana Club, the ABH, opened in 1930<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1961/03/24/118030042.html?pageNumber=52|title=Atlantic Beach Club Sold|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1930/07/20/107112745.html?pdf_redirect=true&site=false|title=HOTEL FOR ATLANTIC BEACH, L.I.|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> and plans were announced for the building of the Casa del Mar(later the Nautilus Hotel<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1962/07/17/82056228.html?pageNumber=42|title=Atlantic Beach Hotel Sold|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>), an apartment hotel, which upon completion became an overnight sensation and, in August 1930, the new homeowners in Atlantic Beach joined together and formed the Atlantic Beach Property Owner's Association. The United States Olympic Diving team practiced at the Atlantic Beach Hotel<nowiki/>https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1983/08/07/162062.html?pageNumber=256.\n\nThe community attracted the wealthy due to its resort atmosphere produced by the beach clubs. Atlantic Beach was frequented by [[Jimmy Walker|Mayor Jimmy Walker]] who was a personal friend of Village founder William L. Austin, [[Jean Arthur]], [[Tallulah Bankhead]], [[Guy Lombardo]], [[Peter Lorre]], and other members of the [[Social Register|social register]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/07/16/91581779.html?pageNumber=14|title=SEEN AT THE ATLANTIC BEACH CLUB|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1983/08/07/162062.html?pageNumber=256|title=IF YOU'RE THINKING OF LIVING IN: ATLANTIC BEACH|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Atlantic beach is sometimes referred to as the \u201cPalm Beach of New York\u201d, and is to many a summer paradise.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1937/10/17/archives/plan-new-beach-club-inwood-members-purchase-a-site-at-atlantic.html|title=PLAN NEW BEACH CLUB; Inwood Members Purchase a Site at Atlantic Beach|date=1937-10-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/25/opinion/l-atlantic-beach-memoir-249378.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Atlantic Beach Memoir|date=2003-06-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Later on, in the 1960s, the village was frequented by the [[Kennedy family|Kennedy's]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/09/07/archives/throngs-mob-kennedy-at-beach.html|title=Throngs Mob Kennedy at Beach|date=1964-09-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The village was a big draw when the Hamptons were just a pile of sand.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wilgoren|first=Jodi|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/25/nyregion/summer-places-the-beach-club-sea-sand-and-seven-card-stud.html|title=SUMMER PLACES: The Beach Club; Sea, Sand and Seven-Card Stud|date=1999-07-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Prohibition ===\nDuring Prohibition, local swimmers would guide [[Dory|dories]](Small boats) full of alcohol to shore from Canadian Ships anchored nearby<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.longislandexchange.com/towns/atlantic-beach/|title=Atlantic Beach|website=www.longislandexchange.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>.\n<br />\n\n=== World War II ===\nAtlantic Beach became of vital importance to the government during World War II. A 120 foot concrete lookout tower was constructed at the tip of [https://www.silverpointclub.com/ Silverpoint] with both the bridge and its access to Silverpoint being designated as emergency military routes in time of war. During this time, homeowners also patrolled the beaches for signs of enemy submarines. By the end of World War II, Atlantic Beach had become a summer mecca with thousands of city dweller clogging what were then only local streets  through both the Rockaways and the Five towns<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1942/06/14/119451470.html?pageNumber=196|title=At Atlantic Beach|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" />. Beach clubs helped to support the war effort by abiding by dim-out requirements, offering bus service, installing bike racks, and some even allowed their guest to stay overnight(Which now is strictly forbidden)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1942/06/28/99332838.html?pdf_redirect=true&site=false|title=At Atlantic Beach|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1942/07/12/85564426.html?pageNumber=165|title=Cycling at Atlantic Beach|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. The Ocean Club(at the time known as the Ocean Club of Forest Hills) held an acclaimed social events in support of the war effort<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1942/06/21/105171091.html?pageNumber=172|title=Atlantic Beach Parties|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n=== The New Atlantic Beach Bridge ===\nOn October 14, 1950, a groundbreaking ceremony for the new [[Atlantic Beach Bridge]] was held and the ribbon cutting ceremony for the new bridge was held on May 10,1952.\n\n==== The New Boardwalk ====\nIn June of 1953, the reconstruction of the Boardwalk from The Plaza to Putnam was completed. This is the same boardwalk that stands today. This boardwalk was half the width and shorter than the prior boardwalk.\n\n=== Resistance to Development ===\nMany of the beach club\u2019s owners have tried to buy additional lots in the village, however, most attempts has been rebuffed by the village board; the residents are staunchly opposed to any development that is not in-line with the character of the village, even until this day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.villageofatlanticbeach.com/departments/|title=Departments|date=2015-06-30|website=Village of Atlantic Beach|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=John C. Devlrn Special to The New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/12/21/archives/proposal-for-parkat-silver-point-being-studied-plan-for-development.html|title=Proposal for Park at Silver Point Being Studied|date=1975-12-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Cotsalas|first=Valerie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/08/realestate/08lizo.html|title=A Village Is Thinking Beyond Cabanas|date=2007-04-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Monahan|first=Sharon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/27/nyregion/atlantic-beach-upset-by-beach-club-project.html|title=Atlantic Beach Upset By Beach Club Project|date=1990-05-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liherald.com/stories/sparks-fly-over-new-atlantic-beach-club,121873|title=Sparks fly over new Atlantic Beach club|website=Herald Community Newspapers|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1990/05/27/417390.html?pageNumber=202|title=Atlantic Beach Upset By Beach Club Project|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> A relatively recent attempt to develop beachside condos was supported by former [[Al D'Amato|Senator D'Amato]], however, it failed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lambert|first=Bruce|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/26/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/26mainli.html|title=D\u2019Amato a Heavyweight in Condo Plan Dispute|date=2007-08-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Additionally, residents have opposed the construction of an [[Eruv]], since Atlantic Beach residents do not want Atlantic Beach to be overrun like Lawrence and Cedarhurst have been<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1989/11/26/issue.html|title=TimesMachine: Sunday November 26, 1989 - NYTimes.com|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Monahan|first=Sharon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/11/26/nyregion/atlantic-beach-split-by-sabbath-border.html|title=Atlantic Beach Split By Sabbath Border|date=1989-11-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>.\n\n=== Fight for Incorporation ===\nBefore incorporation in 1962, the residents were banded together in a property owners\u2019 association. Before the incorporation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1958/08/29/79698222.html?pdf_redirect=true&site=false|title=VILLAGE STATUS SOUGHT; Atlantic Beach to Request Nassau Incorporation|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pbDFOHLrN60C&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&q=Atlantic+beach&hl=en|title=Records & Briefs New York State Appellate DIvision|language=en}}</ref>, it turned over the deeds to the community\u2019s beaches to the Town of Hempstead and for a while, everything was fine.&nbsp;However, according to Mayor Lager \u201c, the town tried to extend the use of the beaches to everyone in the town and we fought it<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1968/08/12/76961344.html?pdf_redirect=true&site=false|title=Acquiring of L.I. Beach For Public Use Is Urged|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. The town's response to our objections was, in effect, \u2018Sue us'. So we sought permission to be incorporated as a village from the county<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liherald.com/stories/Happy-50th-Atlantic-Beach,41587|title=Happy 50th, Atlantic Beach|website=Herald Community Newspapers|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> and when we finally won our village status the deeds automatically reverted to the village.\u201d The Village held its first elections in June 1962. Fred Lager was the mayor for the first 28 years until 1996. Initially, they were not granted zoning powers,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kellerman|first=Vivien|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/10/25/nyregion/nassau-villages-fight-for-zoning-rights.html|title=Nassau Villages Fight for Zoning Rights|date=1998-10-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Burghardt|first=Linda F.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/01/nyregion/the-legacies-they-left-966312.html|title=The Legacies They Left|date=2006-01-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> however, zoning powers were fought for,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Katz|first=Debra Morgenstern|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/01/nyregion/atlantic-beach-in-void-over-zoning-power.html|title=Atlantic Beach in Void Over Zoning Power|date=2000-10-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and taken over by the village in 2002.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ain|first=Stewart|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/03/nyregion/in-brief-atlantic-beach-is-closer-to-local-zoning-power.html|title=IN BRIEF; Atlantic Beach Is Closer To Local Zoning Power|date=2002-03-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Katz|first=Debra Morgenstern|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/11/17/nyregion/victory-is-sweet-for-atlantic-beach.html|title=Victory Is Sweet For Atlantic Beach|date=2002-11-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rather|first=John|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/10/26/realestate/if-you-re-thinking-of-living-in-atlantic-beach-ny-village-that-doubles-as-resort.html|title=If You're Thinking of Living In/Atlantic Beach, N.Y.; Village That Doubles as Resort|date=2003-10-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As of 2011, Atlantic Beach is the only village on the island that has been incorporated since 1938<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/resolutions/2011/k1604|title=K1604|date=2015-10-03|website=NY State Senate|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1962/05/30/90167869.html|title=Atlantic Beach Is Upheld On Incorporation Vote|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>.   The Atlantic Beach Village Office at 60 park street officially opened on November 18, 1962.\n\n=== Modern History ===\nThe new Atlantic Beach Village Hall at 65 The Plaza officially opened on June 6, 1971.\n\nDuring the 1970s, a player for The New York Ranger's died in Atlantic Beach following a fight with one of his fellow players.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=Gerald Eskenazi Special to The New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/09/archives/nassau-grand-jury-exonerates-stewart-after-a-hearing-on-sawchuks.html|title=Nassau Grand Jury Exonerates Stewart After a Hearing on Sawchuk's Death|date=1970-06-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Eskenazi|first=Gerald|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/03/archives/nassau-grand-jury-will-hear-testimony-on-sawchuks-death.html|title=Nassau Grand Jury Will Hear Testimony on Sawchuk's Death|date=1970-06-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s there was controversy regarding allegations by a geologist that NYC was dumping sludge and oil, that allegedly affected Atlantic Beach<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1974/08/17/79373634.html?pdf_redirect=true&site=false|title=Atlantic Beach Is Embroiled in Bitter Controversy Over Sludge; 2,000 Village Residents Doctors Surveyed Business Reported Off|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1975/06/29/91184589.html?pdf_redirect=true&site=false|title=Beach Water Here Is Improving; Check on Beaches Here Finds Water Improving|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1974/04/07/106855798.html?pdf_redirect=true&site=false|title=Ocean Off L.I. Is Termed Biggest Dumping Area in Nation; Ocean Off L.I. Is Termed Biggest Dump in Nation|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1984, Atlantic Beach's Ocean Club was sued for allegedly discriminating against Jewish Guest and Jewish Applicants. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/602/489/1634020/|title=PEOPLE OF STATE OF NY ETC. v. Ocean Club, 602 F. Supp. 489 (E.D.N.Y. 1984)|website=Justia Law|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, many of the celebrities and summer residents moved out towards the Hamptons. Some residents from [[Long Beach, New York|Long Beach]] moved into Atlantic Beach as they became wealthier.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Geist|first=William E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/04/29/nyregion/hockey-rivalry-splits-long-beach.html|title=Hockey Rivalry Splits Long Beach|date=1981-04-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|last2=Times|first2=Special To the New York|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, an African American resident of the village named Alfred Jermaine Ewell was beaten up and hospitalized after a [[Lawrence, Nassau County, New York|Lawrence]] public school graduation event in the village.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lyall|first=Sarah|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/06/07/nyregion/atlantic-beach-struggles-to-explain-assault-on-black-youth.html|title=Atlantic Beach Struggles to Explain Assault on Black Youth|date=1991-06-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Later, [[Al Sharpton|Reverend Al Sharpton]] bussed in people and led a march from the town of [[Inwood, New York|Inwood t]]<nowiki/>o Atlantic Beach;<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Lyall|first=Sarah|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/06/09/nyregion/sharpton-gets-mixed-reception-in-protest-march-at-atlantic-beach.html|title=Sharpton Gets Mixed Reception in Protest March at Atlantic Beach|date=1991-06-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He received mix results, as Atlantic Beach is a very open and welcoming community. Additionally, the boy's mother decided not to partake in the march.<ref name=\":1\" /> Later, people were tried, and a man was found guilty of the attack.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wolff|first=Craig|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/06/06/nyregion/3-arrested-in-beating-of-a-black.html|title=3 Arrested In Beating Of a Black|date=1991-06-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=McQuiston|first=John T.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/22/nyregion/man-guilty-of-attacking-black-athlete.html|title=Man Guilty Of Attacking Black Athlete|date=1992-11-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Stephen Mahler took over from Fred Lager, as mayor. Mayor Lager was the first mayor of the incorporated village of Atlantic Beach<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.liherald.com/fivetowns/stories/atlantic-beach-salutes-former-mayor,69901?|title=Atlantic Beach salutes former mayor|website=Herald Community Newspapers|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2007 It was rumored that [[Donald Trump|President Donald Trump's]] [[The Trump Organization|Trump Organization]] and Toll Brothers wanted to develop the oceanfront, however this has not come to fruition.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2012, Atlantic beach was severely impacted by [[Hurricane Sandy]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stormrecovery.ny.gov/regional-communities/village-atlantic-beach-and-east-atlantic-beach|title=Village of Atlantic Beach and East Atlantic Beach {{!}} Governor\u2019s Office of Storm Recovery (GOSR)|website=stormrecovery.ny.gov|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-york/longbeach/atlantic-beach-club-destroyed-sandy-hosts-grand-reopening|title=Atlantic Beach Club Destroyed by Sandy Hosts Grand Reopening|date=2016-07-01|website=Long Beach, NY Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weather.gov/okx/HurricaneSandy|title=Hurricane Sandy|last=US Department of Commerce|first=NOAA|website=www.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nMany young buyers, including people from Manhattan\u2019s [[Upper East Side]], have snapped up Atlantic Beach houses as they grew tired of commuting three or more hours to the [[The Hamptons|Hamptons]] or the [[Jersey Shore]]. However, there are only three oceanfront homes in the Village, most of the homes are either not on the water, or they face [[Reynolds Channel|Reynold\u2019s channel]]. There are many summer-time rentals in the village.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Merkin|first=Daphne|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/08/garden/08summer.html|title=A Summer Rental of One\u2019s Own|date=2010-07-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.annettcellis.com/idx/?lid=c0edc9c55a1b471380d767151f9e9e52|title=Search MLS Listings \u2013 Annett C. Ellis Realty, Inc. 11509|website=annettcellis.com|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, George Pappas assumed the Mayorship from Stephen Mahler, who had served as Mayor for the previous 18 years<ref name=\":5\" />.\n\nDuring the summer of 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/boruch-dayan-emmes/432338/tragic-update-body-and-paddelboard-of-gary-turkel-zl-recovered-in-atlantic-ocean.html|title=TRAGIC UPDATE: Body And PaddelBoard Of Gary Turkel Z'L Recovered In Atlantic Ocean|last=Editor|first=Y. W.|date=2016-06-17|website=The Yeshiva World|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> a paddle-boarder named Gary Turkel from the village was found dead at sea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/2016/06/17/united-states/body-of-missing-jewish-paddleboarder-found-30-miles-off-long-island|title=Body of missing Jewish paddleboarder found 30 miles off Long Island|date=2016-06-17|website=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/news/breaking-news/342889/local-patrol-continues-search-for-missing-ny-jewish-paddleboarder/|title=Local Patrol Continues Search for Missing NY Jewish Paddleboarder|last=JTAJune 16|last2=2016LinkedIn|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> Billionaire, former NYC Mayor, and Former Presidential Candidate [[Michael Bloomberg|Mike Bloomberg]], spoke at his funeral.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uwskids.wordpress.com/2016/06/19/gary-turkel-a-husband-father-leader-and-mensch-to-be-honored/|title=Gary Turkel \u2013 a husband, father, leader and mensch to be honored|last=valeriegerstein|date=2016-06-19|website=The Blog for families on the Upper West Side|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nThere are still many beach clubs along the beach. There is also an old-age home called the Nautilus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=Harry V. Forgeron Special To the New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/03/27/archives/nautilus-coop-at-atlantic-beach-smoothes-waves-of-discontent-a-coop.html|title=Nautilus Co-op at Atlantic Beach Smoothes Waves of Discontent; A CO-OP HOTEL FINDS QUIET SEAS|date=1966-03-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> A development called Pebble Cove was built along the Ocean between Putnam Blvd and Vernon Avenue. Pebble Cove is a 48-town-house complex with gated security and a swimming pool.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Brauchli|first=Marcus W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/08/07/realestate/if-you-re-thinking-of-living-in-atlantic-beach.html|title=If You're Thinking of Living in: Atlantic Beach|date=1983-08-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=Dudley Dalton Special to The New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/05/16/archives/atlantic-beach-strives-to-preserve-its-40yearold-proprieties.html|title=Atlantic Beach Strives to Preserve Its 40\u2010Year\u2010Old Proprieties|date=1971-05-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Kellerman|first=Vivien|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/13/realestate/if-you-re-thinking-living-atlantic-beach-li-barrier-island-family-aura.html|title=If You're Thinking of Living In/ Atlantic Beach, L.I.; On a Barrier Island, a Family Aura|date=1998-09-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nDuring the summer of 2019, there was an article about an Uber driver who kidnapped a girl from Atlantic Beach.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gold|first=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/27/nyregion/uber-driver-kidnapping.html|title=Every Parent\u2019s Nightmare: A Teenage Girl and an Uber Driver With His Own Plan|date=2019-08-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-york/longbeach/uber-driver-kidnapped-teenage-passenger-assault-her-nassau-da|title=Uber Driver Kidnapped Teenage Passenger To Assault Her: Nassau DA|date=2019-08-22|website=Merrick, NY Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/york-uber-driver-arraigned-allegedly-kidnapping-teen-girl/story?id=65146386|title=New York Uber driver arraigned for allegedly kidnapping teen girl during ride home from Sweet 16: DA|last=News|first=A. B. C.|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/25/long-island-teen-escapes-kidnap-attempt-by-uber-driver/|title=Long Island teen escapes kidnap attempt by Uber driver|last=Hechtman|first=Michael|date=2019-08-25|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1970= 1640\n|1980= 1775\n|1990= 1933\n|2000= 1986\n|2010= 1891\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=1907\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=December 29, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html |title=Census of Population and Housing |publisher=Census.gov |accessdate=June 4, 2015 }}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref> of 2000, there were 1,986 people, 766 households, and 569 families residing in the village. The [[population density]] was 4,114.8 people per square mile (1,597.5/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 954 housing units at an average density of 1,976.6 per square mile (767.4/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the village was 96.98% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.70% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.81% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.55% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.96% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.97% of the population.\n\nThere were 766 households out of which 27.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 64.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.2% had a female householder with no husband present, and 25.6% were non-families. 22.5% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.48 and the average family size was 2.93.\n\nIn the village, the population was spread out with 19.5% under the age of 18, 5.0% from 18 to 24, 21.6% from 25 to 44, 31.7% from 45 to 64, and 22.1% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 47 years. For every 100 females, there were 93.9 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 87.3 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the village was $85,122, and the median income for a family was $93,647. Males had a median income of $67,583 versus $49,750 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the village was $44,035. About 3.9% of families and 5.6% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 6.5% of those under age 18 and 2.2% of those age 65 or over.\n\n== Notable Residents ==\n\n*[[Vanderbilt family|The Vanderbilts]] and [[Ethel Barrymore]] had houses in the village during the 1920's\n*[[Al Goodman]] bought a home in the village in 1944.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1944/02/16/archives/al-goodman-buys-home-atlantic-beach-property-goes-to-orchestra.html|title=AL GOODMAN BUYS HOME; Atlantic Beach Property Goes to Orchestra Leader|date=1944-02-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*[[Anthony Carfano]], group leader of the [[Genovese crime family|Luciano crime family]], resided in the village at5e and later at 83 Clayton Avenue in West Atlantic Beach<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gangstersinc.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=6329524%3ABlogPost%3A68981&commentId=6329524%3AComment%3A76175&xg_source=activity|title=The Life & Death of Anthony Carfano: Temptation of Revenge|last=Posted by Gangsters Inc. on February 11|first=2016 at 11:00am|last2=Blog|first2=View|website=gangstersinc.ning.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n*[[Michele Miranda]], who assumed leadership of the [[Genovese crime family|Genovese Crime Famil]]<nowiki/>y in 1958, resided in Atlantic Beach<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenewyorkmafia.com/mob-homes/|title=Hidden Mob Paradise|date=2019-11-10|website=The New York Mafia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. Additionally, Lorenzo Brescia, one of his henchmen, lived in Atlantic Beach as well. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=478528875962990&id=272147093267837|title=La Famiglia Genovese|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n*[[Personal relationships of Paul McCartney|Nancy Shevell McCartney]] the third wife of [[Beatle]] [[Paul McCartney]] lived there with her ex-husband [[Bruce Blakeman]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2015/05/16/nancy-shevells-ex-husband-bruce-blakeman-remarries/|title=Nancy Shevell\u2019s ex-husband Bruce Blakeman remarries|last=Team|first=Page Six|date=2015-05-17|website=Page Six|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>rican dating McCartney does not wear a ring and is legally separated from husband|website=Mail Online|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. Nancy is the heiress to The Shevell group, which includes [[New England Motor Freight|New England Motor Freight(NEMF)]] and she is cousins with [[Barbara Walters]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/1998/10/13/secret-agent-man/|title=Secret Agent Man {{!}} The Village Voice|website=www.villagevoice.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=473240f0-79c7-11ea-918b-9f7bb12bf9c2&url=L3Byb2ZpbGUvY29tcGFueS80NTMwODY5WjpVUw==|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/paul-mccartney-didn-break-girlfriend-marriage-article-1.257032|title=Paul McCartney didn't break up girlfriend's marriage|last=CONNOR|first=MIKE JACCARINO, STEPHANIE GASKELL, TRACY|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sir-paul-mccartney-marries-nancy-245956|title=Sir Paul McCartney Marries Nancy Shevell in London|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2011/08/how-trucker-girl-nancy-shevell-became-lady-mccartney/|title=How Trucker-Girl Nancy Shevell Became Lady McCartney|date=2011-08-09|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.easternfreightways.com/myron.html|title=Eastern|website=www.easternfreightways.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/paul-mccartney-fiance-nancy-shevell-compared-heather-mills/story?id=13562392|title=Paul McCartney Engaged to Nancy Shevell: Third Time Charmed?|last=News|first=A. B. C.|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2007/11/11/paul-nancys-stolen-kisses/|title=PAUL & NANCY\u2019S STOLEN KISSES|last=Otis|first=Ginger Adams|date=2007-11-11|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Chan|first=Sewell|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/07/nyregion/07beatle.html|title=Former Beatle Linked to Member of M.T.A. Unit|date=2007-11-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>.\n*[[J. Ezra Merkin]] owns a home in the village that at the time of the [[Madoff investment scandal|Bernie Madoff Scandal]], was valued at 1.7 Million Dollar<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2011/09/09/investors-stew-as-madoff-middleman-lives-the-good-life/|title=Investors stew as Madoff middleman lives the good life|last=Whitehouse|first=Kaja|date=2011-09-09|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n*[[Max Stern (businessman)|Max Stern]] and his son Billionaire [[Leonard N. Stern|Leonard Stern]] lived there. Leonard moved out in the 1980s. Max Stern's son Armand lives in the village.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/06/10/archives/armand-lindenbaum-weds-jean-herskovits-at-the-plaza.html|title=Armand Lindenbaum Weds Jean Herskovits at the Plaza|date=1966-06-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jewishcenterofatlanticbeach.org/jcab-board.html|title=JCAB Board - The Jewish Center of Atlantic Beach|website=jewishcenterofatlanticbeach.org|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n*[[Henry Swieca]], the billionaire co-founder of [[Highbridge Capital Management|Highbridge Capital Managment,]] is a resident of the village,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitepages.com/name/Henry-Swieca|title=Henry Swieca|website=whitepages.com|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> and has donated money to the local synagogue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://990s.foundationcenter.org/990pf_pdf_archive/137/137437179/137437179_201712_990PF.pdf|title=Sweica Family Foundation 2017 Tax Returns|last=|first=|date=2017|website=Grantmakers.io|access-date=02/20/2020}}</ref>\n\n== Rankings and Distinctions ==\n\n* In 2005 and 2006, Atlantic Beach and its zip code of 11509 was number 318 on Forbes Magazine's list of Most Expensive Zip Codes. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/7/ZIP11509.html|title=11509, Most Expensive ZIP Codes 2006 - Forbes.com|website=www.forbes.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n* In 2007, Atlantic Beach and its zip code of 11509 was number 279 on Forbes Magazine's list of Most Expensive Zip Codes. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/business/lists/2007/7/forbeslife-cx_07zip_11509_ZIP11509.html|title=#279 11509 - Forbes.com|website=www.forbes.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n* In 2010, Atlantic Beach and its zip code of 11509 was number 303 on Forbes Magazine's list of Most Expensive Zip Codes. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/zipcodes/2010/zipspage.html|title=Most Expensive ZIP Codes - Forbes.com|website=www.forbes.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n* In 2011, Atlantic Beach and its zip code of 11509 was number 226 on Forbes Magazine's list of Most Expensive Zip Codes.  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2011/7/zip-codes-11_rank.html|title=America's Most Expensive ZIP Codes List|website=www.forbes.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n* in 2013, Atlantic beach and its zip code of 11509 was number 427 on Forbes Magazine's list of Most Expensive Zip Codes. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/special-report/2013/zip_table/zips_table.html|title=Untitled|website=www.forbes.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n* Atlantic beach was named by [https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/07/25/malibu-darien-newport-rye-americas-richest-beach-towns/39794491/ USA Today] and [https://247wallst.com/special-report/2019/07/22/americas-richest-beach-towns/5/ 247wallst.com]<ref name=\":3\" /> as the 16th richest beach town in America, with a median household income of $131, 964 and an estimated 1,574 residents<ref name=\":2\" />. This does not include seasonal residents, many of whom are substantially wealthier.\n\n<br />\n\n== Wildlife and Geography ==\n\n=== Access and Street Layout ===\nThe blocks are in alphabetical order named after counties in New York State and are in alphabetical order from A-Z, with the exception of X and Z. There are three main roads that intersect these blocks in the Village, Bay Blvd, Park Street, and Ocean Blvd. As Park Street enters into East Atlantic Beach, it becomes Beech Street. The blocks in West Atlantic Beach are from A-G. There are four main roads that intersect these roads, Ocean Blvd, Pacific Blvd, Atlantic Blvd(Continuation of Park Street), and Bay Blvd.\n\nAtlantic beach is connected to the rest of Long Island by the [[Atlantic Beach Bridge]]. Atlantic Beach has the only toll-bridge in Nassau County, the [[Atlantic Beach Bridge]], which charges a $2.00 toll;  [[E-ZPass]] is not accepted. Decals are available for purchase.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ncbaabb.com/|title=NCBA|website=ncbaabb.com|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Ain|first=Stewart|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/25/nyregion/atlantic-beach-bridge-tolls-jobs-and-politics.html|title=Atlantic Beach Bridge: Tolls, Jobs and Politics|date=1999-07-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 1952, the original bridge was replaced by the [[Atlantic Beach Bridge|Nassau County Bridge Authority]]. The toll is somewhat controversial due to allegations of patronage, however, Atlantic Beach residents support it since it helps to control traffic in the village.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Goldman|first=Ari L.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/06/19/archives/long-island-weekly-for-whom-the-atlantic-beach-bridge-tolls-bridge.html|title=For Whom the Atlantic Beach Bridge Tolls?|date=1977-06-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/06/22/archives/brooklyn-pages-bridge-tolls-cut-in-atlantic-beach.html|title=Bridge Tolls Cut In Atlantic Beach|date=1975-06-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Lambert|first=Bruce|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/12/14/nyregion/often-criticized-bridge-agency-votes-to-increase-the-only-toll-on-li.html|title=Often-Criticized Bridge Agency Votes to Increase the Only Toll on L.I.|date=1996-12-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The bridge is notorious for frequently opening to let ships through.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=Ruth Heyman Special to The New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/07/23/archives/atlantic-beach-span-a-bridge-of-sighs-exasperating-ones-beach-span.html|title=Atlantic Beach Span a Bridge of Sighs\u2014Exasperating Ones|date=1972-07-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Recreational Facilities and Parks ===\nAtlantic beach residents have access to a [https://www.abcmoralestennis.com/ 10-court tennis center], that is leased out to a private company. Currently, Resident memberships are $1750 for the 2020 summer season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abcmoralestennis.com/|title=Home {{!}} Atlantic Beach Tennis|website=Atlantic Beach Tenni|language=en|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> The club has been under construction in an effort to make it more luxurious for the residents<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liherald.com/fivetowns/stories/continuing-renovations-hurting-membership-at-atlantic-beach-tennis-center,116751?|title=Continuing renovations hurting membership at Atlantic Beach Tennis Center|website=Herald Community Newspapers|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>.\n\nThere is a 22 foot wide boardwalk by the beach, that runs from Albany to Putnam.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ketcham|first=Diane|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/15/nyregion/different-boardwalks-different-beaches.html|title=Different Boardwalks, Different Beaches|date=1998-11-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThere are a few playgrounds scattered throughout the village. \n\n=== Wildlife  ===\n\n* Atlantic Beach has an artificial Reef located off of its shores <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liherald.com/fivetowns/stories/aiming-to-boost-long-islands-marine-life,117619?|title=Aiming to boost Long Island\u2019s marine life|website=Herald Community Newspapers|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*Atlantic Beach is home to a population of the rare and endangered bird species [[Piping plover|Piping Plovers]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/17/nyregion/l-saving-the-threatened-piping-plover-901188.html|title=Saving the Threatened Piping Plover|date=1988-07-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>[[File:Piping Plovers Atlantic Beach New York.jpg|thumb|A picture of rare [[Piping plover|Piping Plovers]] in Atlantic Beach, New York.]]\n\n==Government and politics==\n{{Expand section|date=December 2009}}\nPolitically, Atlantic Beach leans [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] but only very slightly. In the 2008 presidential election Republican [[John McCain]] won Atlantic Beach over Democrat [[Barack Obama]] 52%-47%.\n\nThe Atlantic Beach Fire District is responsible for providing fire and emergency ambulance services for the majority of the village.  Atlantic Beach, however, does not have its own fire department, and therefore contracts out fire protection to the [[Long Beach Fire Department (New York)|Long Beach Fire Department]], with the exception of the Silver Point Beach Club and Sun and Surf Beach Club, which are protected by the Inwood Fire Department.\n\nEmergency ambulance services are provided by a combination of Atlantic Beach Rescue Squad<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liherald.com/fivetowns/stories/atlantic-beach-rescue-responds-to-the-calls-for-help,119534?|title=Atlantic Beach Rescue responds to the calls for help|website=Herald Community Newspapers|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liherald.com/stories/atlantic-beach-rescue-trains-for-the-usual-and-unusual,117223|title=Atlantic Beach Rescue trains for the usual and unusual|website=Herald Community Newspapers|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> and the Long Beach Fire Department, again, with the exception of the Silver Point and Sun and Surf Beach Clubs, which are covered by the Inwood Fire Department<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1989/12/31/471589.html?pageNumber=181|title=Atlantic Beach Seeks Fire Protection Pact|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. The Atlantic Beach Rescue Unit officially went into service in 1975<ref name=\":4\" />.\n\nPolice protection is provided by the 4th Precinct of the [[Nassau County Police Department]].  The village also maintains its own small civilian security patrol.\nAtlantic Beach is an incorporated village, and has its own Zoning and Building Depts, including a Board of Zoning Appeals\n. New York State Assemblyperson [[Melissa Miller (politician)|Melissa Miller]] (R - 20th District), elected in 2016, was born, raised and currently still lives in Atlantic Beach.\n* Atlantic Beach is a Village in the [[Hempstead, New York|Town Of Hempstead]] and is represented by Councilman [[Bruce Blakeman]] (3rd R).\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Atlantic Beach Bridge]]\n* [[New York State Route 878|Route 878]], which leads to Atlantic Beach\n*[[East Atlantic Beach, New York|East Atlantic beach]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n\n* https://www.villageofatlanticbeach.com/\n* https://www.newsday.com/long-island/nassau/hempstead-ny/atlantic-beach-ny\n* https://www.longisland.com/atlantic-beach/news/\n{{Nassau County, New York}}{{HempsteadNY}}\n{{Long Beach, New York}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hempstead, New York]]\n[[Category:Villages in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Villages in Nassau County, New York]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atlantic_Beach,_New_York"}
