alified\n\n===Final===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank !! Name !! Nationality !! Time (hand) !! Notes\n|-\n|{{gold1}} ||align=left|[[Harrison Dillard]] || align=left| {{FlagIOC|USA|1948 Summer}} || 10.3 || '''=[[List of Olympic records in athletics|OR]]''' \n|-\n|{{silver2}} ||align=left|[[Barney Ewell]] || align=left| {{FlagIOC|USA|1948 Summer}} || 10.4 || ''' '''\n|-\n| {{Bronze3}} ||align=left|[[Lloyd LaBeach]] || align=left| {{FlagIOC|PAN|1948 Summer}} || 10.6 || \n|-\n| 4 ||align=left| [[Alastair McCorquodale]] ||align=left| {{FlagIOC|GBR|1948 Summer}} ||  ||\n|-\n| 5 ||align=left| [[Mel Patton]] ||align=left| {{FlagIOC|USA|1948 Summer}} ||  || \n|-\n| 6 ||align=left| [[McDonald Bailey]] ||align=left| {{FlagIOC|GBR|1948 Summer}} ||  ||\n|}\n\n'''Key''': =OR = Equalled Olympic record\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Organising Committee for the XIV Olympiad, The (1948). [http://library.la84.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1948/OR1948.pdf The Official Report of the Organising Committee for the XIV Olympiad]. ''[[LA84 Foundation]]''. Retrieved 4 September 2016.\n\n{{Olympics100metres}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Athletics at the 1948 Summer Olympics - Men's 100 metres}}\n[[Category:Athletics at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:100 metres at the Olympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Men's 100 metres\n|games = 1948 Summer\n|image = \n|caption = \n|venue = [[Wembley Stadium]]<br>[[London]], [[England]]\n|dates = 30 July 1948 (heats, quarterfinals)<br/>31 July 1948 (semifinals, final)\n|competitors = 63\n|nations = 33\n|win_value = 10.3 seconds\n|gold = [[Harrison Dillard]]\n|goldNOC = USA\n|silver = [[Barney Ewell]]\n|silverNOC = USA\n|bronze = [[Lloyd LaBeach]]\n|bronzeNOC = PAN\n|prev=[[Athletics at the 1936 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres|1936]]\n|next=[[Athletics at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres|1952]]\n}}\n\n[[Image:TV-icon-2.svg|thumb|110px|'''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WhXmwCqvz8M Official Video Highlights]''']]\n\n{{AthleticsAt1948SummerOlympics}}\n\nThe '''men's [[100 metres]]''' [[Sprint (running)|sprint]] event at the '''[[Athletics at the 1948 Summer Olympics|1948 Olympic Games]]''' in [[London, England]], we held at [[Wembley Stadium]] on 30 and 31 July.<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1948/ATH/mens-100-metres.html |title=Athletics at the 1948 London Summer Games: Men's 100 metres |accessdate=6 June 2017 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>  The final was won by [[United States|American]] Harrison Dillard, in a [[photo finish]]. This was the first time a photo finish camera was used at an Olympic Games.<ref>Jackson, Peter (24 July 2012). [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18782392 \"London's three Olympic Games compared\"], '' BBC News''.</ref> The photo finish equipment consisted of a photoelectric cell, called the Magic Eye, produced by Swiss watchmaker Omega and a slit photography camera produced by the British Race Finish Recording Company<ref>https://secondtime.com/blog/omega-the-olympics-and-the-innovations-required-to-time-the-earths-best/</ref>.\n\n==Records==\nPrior to the competition, the existing World and Olympic records were as follows.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''[[World record progression 100 metres men|World record]]'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Jesse Owens]]|USA}}\n|rowspan=2 align=center|'''10.2 s'''\n|[[Chicago]], [[United States]]\n|20 June 1936\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Harold Davis (sprinter)|Harold Davis]]|USA}}\n|[[Compton, California|Compton]], United States\n|6 June 1941\n|-\n|'''Olympic record'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Jesse Owens]]|USA}}\n|'''10.3 s'''\n|[[Berlin]], [[Germany]]\n|2 August 1936\n|}\n\n==Schedule==\n<small>All times are [[British Summer Time]] ([[UTC+1]]).</small>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Time\n!\n|-\n|Friday, 30 July 1948 ||'''15:00<br>17:30'''||'''Round 1<br>Round 2'''\n|-\n|style=background:lemonchiffon|Satur