{"title_page": "Athletics New Zealand", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox sport governing body\n|name         = Athletics New Zealand\n|abbrev       = ANZ\n|logo         = Athletics New Zealand Logo.png\n|logosize     = 204px\n|sport        = [[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]]\n|category     = \n|image        =\n|caption      =\n|jurisdiction = Incorporated Society \n|founded      = {{Start date|1887}}\n|aff          = [[IAAF]]\n|affdate      = 1932\n|region       = [[Oceania Athletics Association|OAA]]\n|regionyear   =\n|headquarters = [[Auckland]]\n|location     =\n|membership = \n|president    = [[Dianne Zorn|Dianne Rodger]]\n|chairman     = \n|chairperson  = [[Annette Purvis]]\n|chair        = \n|chiefexec    =\n|vicepresident = [[Ian Babe]]\n|secretary    = \n|coach        =\n|womenscoach  =\n|key staff    =\n|operating income =\n|sponsor      =\n|year closed  =\n|replaced     = New Zealand Amateur Athletic Association\n|prevfounded  =\n|url          = http://www.athletics.org.nz/\n|countryflag  = New Zealand\n|countryflag2 =\n|countryflag3 =\n}}\n'''Athletics New Zealand''' (ANZ) is the national governing body for [[athletics (sport)|athletics]] in [[New Zealand]]. This includes responsibility for [[Track and field]], [[cross country running]], [[road running]] and [[racewalking]].<ref name=iaaf_1>\n{{ Citation \n| last = \n| first = \n| date = \n| title = Athletics New Zealand\n| url = http://www.iaaf.org/about-iaaf/structure/member-federations/oceania#NZL\n| publisher = [[IAAF]]\n| page = \n| language = \n| accessdate = January 24, 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe organisation was founded in 1887 as the New Zealand Amateur Athletic Association (NZAAA). The first national championships were held the following year in 1888.  In 1989, the current name was adopted.<ref name=teara_01>\n{{ Citation \n| last = \n| first = \n| date = \n| title = Story: Athletics - Page 1 \u2013 The sport of athletics\n| url = http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/athletics/page-1\n| publisher = [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]]\n| page = \n| language = \n| accessdate = January 24, 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== Structure ==\nThere are 11 regional athletics associations supporting 179 clubs with approximately 22,000 registered members including athletes, coaches and volunteers.<ref>[http://www.athletics.org.nz/Portals/24/Files/Administration/Annual%20reports%20Pre%202009/ATHNZ_2017-18%20Ann%20Report%203.3MB.pdf ''Athletics New Zealand Annual Report 2018''], retrieved 22 March 2019</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+New Zealand Regional Athletics Associations\n|<small>Athletics Northland Inc</small>\n|<small>[https://www.sporty.co.nz/athletics Athletics Northland]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Auckland Inc</small> \n|<small>[http://www.athleticsauckland.co.nz www.athleticsauckland.co.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Waikato Bay of Plenty Inc</small> \n|<small>[http://www.athleticswaikatobayofplenty.org.nz www.athleticswaikatobayofplenty.org.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Taranaki Inc</small>\n|<small>[http://www.athleticstaranaki.org.nz www.athleticstaranaki.org.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Hawkes Bay Gisborne Inc</small> \n|<small>[https://www.sporty.co.nz/athleticshbgisborne/Home Hawkes Bay Gisborne Athletics]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Manawatu Wanganui Inc</small> \n|<small>[http://www.pnahc.org.nz PNAHC] [http://www.athleticswanganui.co.nz Wanganui Athletics]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Wellington Inc</small>\n|<small>[http://www.athleticswellington.org.nz www.athleticswellington.org.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Tasman Inc</small>\n|<small>[https://athleticsnelson.co.nz/ athleticsnelson]<small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Canterbury Inc</small> \n|<small>[http://www.athleticscanterbury.org.nz www.athleticscanterbury.org.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Otago Inc</small>\n|<small>[http://www.athleticsotago.co.nz www.athleticsotago.co.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Southland Inc</small> \n|<small>[http://www.athleticssouthland.co.nz www.athleticssouthland.co.nz]</small>\n|}\n\n==Affiliations==\nANZ is the national member federation for [[New Zealand]] in the following international organisations:\n*[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] (IAAF)\n*[[Oceania Athletic Association]] (OAA)\nAthletics New Zealand is part of the following national organisations:\n*[[New Zealand Olympic Committee]]\n\n== National records ==\nANZ maintains the [[New Zealand records in athletics]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sport in New Zealand]]\n*[[Sport and Recreation New Zealand]]\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/A/AthleticstrackAndField/AthleticstrackAndField/en ATHLETICS\u2013TRACK AND FIELD - 1966 Encyclopaedia of New Zealand]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.athletics.org.nz/}}\n\n{{National Members of the International Association of Athletics Federations}}\n{{Sports governing bodies in New Zealand}}\n\n[[Category:National members of the Oceania Athletics Association|New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Sports governing bodies in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Athletics in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:National governing bodies for athletics]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1887]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-sport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox sport governing body\n|name         = Athletics New Zealand\n|abbrev       = ANZ\n|logo         = Athletics New Zealand Logo.png\n|logosize     = 204px\n|sport        = [[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]]\n|category     = \n|image        =\n|caption      =\n|jurisdiction = Incorporated Society \n|founded      = {{Start date|1887}}\n|aff          = [[IAAF]]\n|affdate      = 1932\n|region       = [[Oceania Athletics Association|OAA]]\n|regionyear   =\n|headquarters = [[Auckland]]\n|location     =\n|membership = \n|president    = [[Dianne Zorn|Dianne Rodger]]\n|chairman     = \n|chairperson  = [[Annette Purvis]]\n|chair        = \n|chiefexec    =\n|vicepresident = [[Ian Babe]]\n|secretary    = \n|coach        =\n|womenscoach  =\n|key staff    =\n|operating income =\n|sponsor      =\n|year closed  =\n|replaced     = New Zealand Amateur Athletic Association\n|prevfounded  =\n|url          = http://www.athletics.org.nz/\n|countryflag  = New Zealand\n|countryflag2 =\n|countryflag3 =\n}}\n'''Athletics New Zealand''' (ANZ) is the national governing body for [[athletics (sport)|athletics]] in [[New Zealand]]. This includes responsibility for [[Track and field]], [[cross country running]], [[road running]] and [[racewalking]].<ref name=iaaf_1>\n{{ Citation \n| last = \n| first = \n| date = \n| title = Athletics New Zealand\n| url = http://www.iaaf.org/about-iaaf/structure/member-federations/oceania#NZL\n| publisher = [[IAAF]]\n| page = \n| language = \n| accessdate = January 24, 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe organisation was founded in 1887 as the New Zealand Amateur Athletic Association (NZAAA). The first national championships were held the following year in 1888.  In 1989, the current name was adopted.<ref name=teara_01>\n{{ Citation \n| last = \n| first = \n| date = \n| title = Story: Athletics - Page 1 \u2013 The sport of athletics\n| url = http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/athletics/page-1\n| publisher = [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]]\n| page = \n| language = \n| accessdate = January 24, 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== Structure ==\nThere are 11 regional athletics associations supporting 179 clubs with approximately 22,000 registered members including athletes, coaches and volunteers<ref>[http://www.athletics.org.nz/Portals/24/Files/Administration/Annual%20reports%20Pre%202009/ATHNZ_2017-18%20Ann%20Report%203.3MB.pdf ''Athletics New Zealand Annual Report 2018''], retrieved 22 March 2019</ref>. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+New Zealand Regional Athletics Associations\n|<small>Athletics Northland Inc</small>\n|<small>[https://www.sporty.co.nz/athletics Athletics Northland]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Auckland Inc</small> \n|<small>[http://www.athleticsauckland.co.nz www.athleticsauckland.co.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Waikato Bay of Plenty Inc</small> \n|<small>[http://www.athleticswaikatobayofplenty.org.nz www.athleticswaikatobayofplenty.org.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Taranaki Inc</small>\n|<small>[http://www.athleticstaranaki.org.nz www.athleticstaranaki.org.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Hawkes Bay Gisborne Inc</small> \n|<small>[https://www.sporty.co.nz/athleticshbgisborne/Home Hawkes Bay Gisborne Athletics]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Manawatu Wanganui Inc</small> \n|<small>[http://www.pnahc.org.nz PNAHC] [http://www.athleticswanganui.co.nz Wanganui Athletics]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Wellington Inc</small>\n|<small>[http://www.athleticswellington.org.nz www.athleticswellington.org.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Tasman Inc</small>\n|<small>[https://athleticsnelson.co.nz/ athleticsnelson]<small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Canterbury Inc</small> \n|<small>[http://www.athleticscanterbury.org.nz www.athleticscanterbury.org.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Otago Inc</small>\n|<small>[http://www.athleticsotago.co.nz www.athleticsotago.co.nz]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Athletics Southland Inc</small> \n|<small>[http://www.athleticssouthland.co.nz www.athleticssouthland.co.nz]</small>\n|}\n\n==Affiliations==\nANZ is the national member federation for [[New Zealand]] in the following international organisations:\n*[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] (IAAF)\n*[[Oceania Athletic Association]] (OAA)\nAthletics New Zealand is part of the following national organisations:\n*[[New Zealand Olympic Committee]]\n\n== National records ==\nANZ maintains the [[New Zealand records in athletics]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sport in New Zealand]]\n*[[Sport and Recreation New Zealand]]\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/A/AthleticstrackAndField/AthleticstrackAndField/en ATHLETICS\u2013TRACK AND FIELD - 1966 Encyclopaedia of New Zealand]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.athletics.org.nz/}}\n\n{{National Members of the International Association of Athletics Federations}}\n{{Sports governing bodies in New Zealand}}\n\n[[Category:National members of the Oceania Athletics Association|New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Sports governing bodies in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Athletics in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:National governing bodies for athletics]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1887]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-sport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Athletics_New_Zealand"}
{"title_page": "Athanasius III of Constantinople", "text_new": "{{Infobox saint\n| name = Athanasius III of Constantinople\n| image = St. Afanasy Lubensky.jpeg\n| venerated_in = [[Russian Orthodox Church]]\n| birth_date = 1597\n| birth_place = [[Rethymno|Retimon]], [[Crete]]\n| death_date = 5 (15) April 1654\n| death_place = [[Mhar Monastery]]\n| titles = Saint, [[Enlightener]]\n| canonized_date = 1670s\n| feast_day = Synaxis of Athonite Venerables: 2 (15) May\n| patronage = [[Dubna]], [[Kharkov]]\n| major_shrine = relics at the [[Annunciation Cathedral, Kharkiv|Annunciation Cathedral, Kharkov]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n|name = \n|image =\n|caption=\n|church = [[Church of Constantinople]]\n|archbishop_of = [[List of Ecumenical Patriarchs of Constantinople|Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]]\n|term=25 February 1634 \u2013 early April 1635<br>June 1652 (15 day)\n|term_end=\n|predecessor =[[Cyril Lucaris]], [[Cyril III of Constantinople]]\n|successor=[[Cyril Lucaris]], [[Paisius I of Constantinople]]\n|birth_name=\n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n}}\n\n'''Athanasius III Patellarios''' (born '''Alexios Patellarios''', {{lang-el|\u0391\u03bb\u03ad\u03be\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2}}, {{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0438\u0439 \u041f\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0440\u0438\u0439}};<ref>in Russian tradition also known as '''Enlightener Athanasius of Tsargrad (the Sitting), Wonderworker of Lubensk''' and '''Athanasius of Kharkov'''</ref> 1597 \u2013 5 April 1654) was the [[Patriarch of Constantinople]] in 1634, 1635 and 1652. Before his patriarchate Athanasius was [[metropolitan bishop|metropolitan]] of [[Thessaloniki]]. He participated at [[Patriarch Nikon]]'s book editing reforms in 1653.\n\nAthanasius was canonized as an ''Enlightener'' into the Synaxis of Athonite Venerables by the [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian Church]] in the 1670s. His feast date is on 2 (15) May, on the 2nd Week after [[Pentecost]], canonized alongside [[Athanasius the Great]].\n[[File:\u0410\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0445 \u0426\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0430.jpg|thumb|left|170px|''Enlightener Athanasius, Patriarch of Constantinople, in the Lubensk Monastery, he who rested sitting.'' [[Russian icon]], 17th century]]\n\n== Biography ==\nAlexios was born to a noble family with roots dating back to the [[Paleologos]] Dynasty. His father Georgios was a scientist and publisher, and his elder brother Eustaphios was a physician. For 26 years he lived in [[Crete]] in the [[Arkadi Monastery]], which was then under [[Venice|Venetian]] rule, and received there his education. Alexios knew well [[philosophy]], [[Ancient Greek]], [[Latin]], [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Arab language|Arab]] and [[Italian language]].\n\nIn 1631 Alexios was consecrated as [[metropolitan bishop|metropolitan]] of [[Thessaloniki]]; he was under patronage of Patriarch [[Cyril Lucaris]]. In early 1634, a third opposition against Lucaris regarding the publication of ''Eastern Confession of the Christian faith'' on March 1629 was formed in [[Fener|Fanari]], as the document had [[Calvinism|Calvinist]] theological lines. In February 1634, Athanasius became [[Patriarch of Constantinople]] and was [[enthronement|enthroned]] on 25 March.\n\nAfter several days he was dethroned by Cyril Lucaris, who returned from prison. Athanasius then escaped to the [[Mount Athos|Athos]], where he built the [[skete]] (where in 1849 the Russian St. Andrew skete was founded), which kept the icon ''Consolation in Sorrow and Grief'' (\u0412 \u0441\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0435\u0445 \u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0445 \u0423\u0442\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435). After his second deposition in 1635, Athanasius went to [[Italy]], staying in [[Ancona]] and [[Venice]]. [[Pope of Rome]] advised Athanasius to become [[cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]] and accept the [[Credo]] with the [[Filioque]], but the saint declined. In 1637 Athanasius was called to Constantinople. On 26 June 1638, after Lucaris was strangled by the request of [[Murad IV]], Athanasius became a pretender to the patriarchate. [[Parthenius I of Constantinople|Parthenius of Constantinople]], Patriarch from 1639 to 1644, required Athanasius to renounce from the patriarchate and return to the Thessaloniki cathedra. Because of the [[metropolis (religious jurisdiction)|metropolis]]' taxes, Athanasius was imprisoned twice, and asked the Russian Tsar [[Michael I of Russia|Michael I]] for charity.\n\nIn 1643 he moved to [[Russian Tsardom|Russia]], but on the way there became ill and stayed in [[Moldavia]], by the [[hospodar]] Vasily Lupu. In [[Gala\u0163i]] he founded the St. Nicholas Monastery as a [[metochion]] of the [[St. Catherine's Monastery]] in [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]]. At that time he wrote the \"Hymn to the Mother of God\", and an [[encomium]] to Lupu.\n\nAthanasius returned to Constantinople in 1652 and took the patriarchate for the third time. Again holding the throne for a short time, Athanasius in July 1652 voluntarily renounced from the patriarchate and ad infinitum left Constantinople. During his last patriarchate, he spoke out a sermon mentioning his dissociation with Catholicism. He again went to Moldavia visiting Lupu in [[Ia\u015fi]], then to [[Chyhyryn|Chigirin]] visiting [[Bohdan Khmelnytsky]]. With the deeds of those people for the Tsar he reached [[Moscow]] on 16 April 1653, and on 22 April visited Tsar [[Alexis of Russia|Alexey]].\n\nThere he lived at the Kirillov metochion, and made his divine service at the [[Novospassky Monastery]] and at the Saviour Cathedral by the [[Terem Palace]]. In July 1653 Athanasius visited the [[Trinity-Sergius Lavra|Trinity Sergiev Monastery]].\n\nAt the request of [[Patriarch Nikon]], Athanasius wrote ''The Ordo of the Episcopal Liturgy in the East'', which underlined the Muscovian edited ''Archieratikon of the Episcopal Service'', which is used by the Russian Church to date.<ref>[http://www.liturgica.ru/bibliot/arkh_bogosl.html M. S. Zheltov. Episcopal Liturgy]</ref> Athanasius delivered the Tsar a notebook in which he stated his main reason for his visit to Moscow; that is, to arouse the Tsar unite with Moldavia and the [[Cossack Hetmanate]] for a future war with the Turks, after which the Tsar should become the new Roman Emperor, and the Moscow Patriarch \u2013 the new Ecumenical Patriarch.\n\nAthanasius is known as a trader of indulgences, which he sold in large quantities in Ukraine and Russia.<ref>[[:ru:\u0413\u0438\u0434\u0443\u043b\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u041f\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447|\u0413\u0438\u0434\u0443\u043b\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u041f\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447]]. /  [http://elib.shpl.ru/ru/nodes/36762-gidulyanov-p-v-zagrobnaya-zhizn-kak-predmet-spekulyatsii-ili-indulgentsii-v-rimsko-katolicheskoy-i-greko-pravoslavnoy-tserkvi-m-ryazan-1930#mode/inspect/page/82/zoom/8 \u0417\u0430\u0433\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044c, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043c\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0443\u043b\u044f\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0434\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0440\u0438\u043c\u0441\u043a\u043e-\u043a\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e-\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0438 / \u041f. \u0412. \u0413\u0438\u0434\u0443\u043b\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432. - \u041c. ; \u0420\u044f\u0437\u0430\u043d\u044c : \u0410\u0442\u0435\u0438\u0441\u0442, 1930. - 176 \u0441. / \u0421. 163, 172]</ref> \n\nBy December 1653 Athanasius moved to Moldavia for the Nicholas Monastery in Gala\u0163i. En route he made a visit to Bohdan Khmelnytsky. In February 1654 he stayed at the Mhar Monastery near Lubensk and died on 5 April on Thomas' Week. He was buried by the [[hegumen]] of the Transfiguration monastery, his body was in a sitting position on the throne under the [[ambon (liturgy)|ambon]].\n\n== Veneration ==\n[[File:Shrine of saint Afanasy Patellary.jpg|thumb|left|170px|Shrine of en. Athanasius at the Lubensk Monastery. [[Lithography]], 1868]]\nOn 1 February 1662, the saint's relics were [[translation (relics)|translated]] due to  the [[metropolitan of Gaza]] [[Paisios Ligaridis]], who, visiting [[Lubensk Monastery]], had a vision of Athanasius during his sleep.\nIn 1672, the Tsar requested [[podyachy]] M. Savin to investigate the wonders from the relics. In the 18th century, manuscripts of his [[hagiography]] and [[Biblical canon|canon]] were preserved at the Lubensk Monastery.\n\nIn 1818, Methodius (Pishnyachevsky), bishop of Poltava, applied the [[Most Holy Synod]] for the canonization of Athanasius, but the application was declined. However the saint's honouring and recorded wonders from his relics continued. In the 1860s, church historian [[Andrey Nikolayevich Muravyov]] created a new hagiography of Athanasius with examples of wonders at his relics.\n\nThe history of the canonization of Athanasius is vague, but the official honouring began in the Russian Church by the end of the 19th century, although [[Yevgeny Golubinsky]] through his works proved that the honouring started between 1672 and 1676 under Joseph (Nelyubovich-Tukalsky), metropolitan of Kiev (Constantinople Orthodox Church).\n\nIn 1922, the Transfiguration cathedral, including the saint's silver throne, was plundered by the [[Bolsheviks]]. The relics were moved to [[Kharkov]] in the 1930s. They were eventually preserved in the city's [[Annunciation Cathedral, Kharkiv|Annunciation Cathedral]] in 1947.\n[[File:Afanasij of Kharkov oil.JPG|thumb|95px|Oil from the relics of Patriarch Athanasius]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n# ''A. V. Ryndina, V. Shapran'' [http://www.pravenc.ru/text/76940.html Athanasius III Patellarios] // ''The Orthodox Encyclopedia.'' vol. IV \u2013 Moscow, 2002. \u2014 pp.&nbsp;20 \u2013 22.\n# [http://www.orthlib.ru/JMP/47_10/07.html St. Athanasius, Patriarch of Tsargrad, Wonderworker of Lubensk] // ''Journal of the Moscow Patriarchate''. 1947, No. 10.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://days.pravoslavie.ru/Life/life975.htm Englightener Athanasius III Patellarios, Patriarch of Tsargrad] on pravoslavie.ru\n* [http://seminaria.virtbox.ru/mon_st1.htm Englightener Athanasius, Wonderworker of Lubensk]. Short hagiography on the Poltava Missionary Spiritual Seminary of the [[Ukrainian Orthodox Church (Moscow Patriarchate)|UOC]]\n\n{{Patriarchs of Constantinople}}\n{{Bishops of Thessalonica}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Russian saints of the Eastern Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:17th-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:Ecumenical Patriarchs of Constantinople]]\n[[Category:17th-century Eastern Orthodox archbishops]]\n[[Category:17th-century people of the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox saint\n| name = Athanasius III of Constantinople\n| image = St. Afanasy Lubensky.jpeg\n| venerated_in = [[Russian Orthodox Church]]\n| birth_date = 1597\n| birth_place = [[Rethymno|Retimon]], [[Crete]]\n| death_date = 5 (15) April 1654\n| death_place = [[Mhar Monastery]]\n| titles = Saint, [[Enlightener]]\n| canonized_date = 1670s\n| feast_day = Synaxis of Athonite Venerables: 2 (15) May\n| patronage = [[Dubna]], [[Kharkov]]\n| major_shrine = relics at the [[Annunciation Cathedral, Kharkiv|Annunciation Cathedral, Kharkov]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n|name = \n|image =\n|caption=\n|church = [[Church of Constantinople]]\n|archbishop_of = [[List of Ecumenical Patriarchs of Constantinople|Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]]\n|term=25 February 1634 \u2013 early April 1635<br>June 1652 (15 day)\n|term_end=\n|predecessor =[[Cyril Lucaris]], [[Cyril III of Constantinople]]\n|successor=[[Cyril Lucaris]], [[Paisius I of Constantinople]]\n|birth_name=\n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n}}\n\n'''Athanasius III Patellarios''' (born '''Alexios Patellarios''', {{lang-el|\u0391\u03bb\u03ad\u03be\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2}}, {{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0438\u0439 \u041f\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0440\u0438\u0439}};<ref>in Russian tradition also known as '''Enlightener Athanasius of Tsargrad (the Sitting), Wonderworker of Lubensk''' and '''Athanasius of Kharkov'''</ref> 1597 \u2013 5 April 1654) was the [[Patriarch of Constantinople]] in 1634, 1635 and 1652. Before his patriarchate Athanasius was [[metropolitan bishop|metropolitan]] of [[Thessaloniki]]. He participated at [[Patriarch Nikon]]'s book editing reforms in 1653.\n\nAthanasius was canonized as an ''Enlightener'' into the Synaxis of Athonite Venerables by the [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian Church]] in the 1670s. His feast date is on 2 (15) May, on the 2nd Week after [[Pentecost]], canonized alongside [[Athanasius the Great]].\n[[File:\u0410\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0445 \u0426\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0430.jpg|thumb|left|170px|''Enlightener Athanasius, Patriarch of Constantinople, in the Lubensk Monastery, he who rested sitting.'' [[Russian icon]], 17th century]]\n\n== Biography ==\nAlexios was born to a noble family with roots dating back to the [[Paleologos]] Dynasty. His father Georgios was a scientist and publisher, and his elder brother Eustaphios was a physician. For 26 years he lived in [[Crete]] in the [[Arkadi Monastery]], which was then under [[Venice|Venetian]] rule, and received there his education. Alexios knew well [[philosophy]], [[Ancient Greek]], [[Latin]], [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Arab language|Arab]] and [[Italian language]].\n\nIn 1631 Alexios was consecrated as [[metropolitan bishop|metropolitan]] of [[Thessaloniki]]; he was under patronage of Patriarch [[Cyril Lucaris]]. In early 1634, a third opposition against Lucaris regarding the publication of ''Eastern Confession of the Christian faith'' on March 1629 was formed in [[Fener|Fanari]], as the document had [[Calvinism|Calvinist]] theological lines. In February 1634, Athanasius became [[Patriarch of Constantinople]] and was [[enthronement|enthroned]] on 25 March.\n\nAfter several days he was dethroned by Cyril Lucaris, who returned from prison. Athanasius then escaped to the [[Mount Athos|Athos]], where he built the [[skete]] (where in 1849 the Russian St. Andrew skete was founded), which kept the icon ''Consolation in Sorrow and Grief'' (\u0412 \u0441\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0435\u0445 \u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0445 \u0423\u0442\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435). After his second deposition in 1635, Athanasius went to [[Italy]], staying in [[Ancona]] and [[Venice]]. [[Pope of Rome]] advised Athanasius to become [[cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]] and accept the [[Credo]] with the [[Filioque]], but the saint declined. In 1637 Athanasius was called to Constantinople. On 26 June 1638, after Lucaris was strangled by the request of [[Murad IV]], Athanasius became a pretender to the patriarchate. [[Parthenius I of Constantinople|Parthenius of Constantinople]], Patriarch from 1639 to 1644, required Athanasius to renounce from the patriarchate and return to the Thessaloniki cathedra. Because of the [[metropolis (religious jurisdiction)|metropolis]]' taxes, Athanasius was imprisoned twice, and asked the Russian Tsar [[Michael I of Russia|Michael I]] for charity.\n\nIn 1643 he moved to [[Russian Tsardom|Russia]], but on the way there became ill and stayed in [[Moldavia]], by the [[hospodar]] Vasily Lupu. In [[Gala\u0163i]] he founded the St. Nicholas Monastery as a [[metochion]] of the [[St. Catherine's Monastery]] in [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]]. At that time he wrote the \"Hymn to the Mother of God\", and an [[encomium]] to Lupu.\n\nAthanasius returned to Constantinople in 1652 and took the patriarchate for the third time. Again holding the throne for a short time, Athanasius in July 1652 voluntarily renounced from the patriarchate and ad infinitum left Constantinople. During his last patriarchate, he spoke out a sermon mentioning his dissociation with Catholicism. He again went to Moldavia visiting Lupu in [[Ia\u015fi]], then to [[Chyhyryn|Chigirin]] visiting [[Bohdan Khmelnytsky]]. With the deeds of those people for the Tsar he reached [[Moscow]] on 16 April 1653, and on 22 April visited Tsar [[Alexis of Russia|Alexey]].\n\nThere he lived at the Kirillov metochion, and made his divine service at the [[Novospassky Monastery]] and at the Saviour Cathedral by the [[Terem Palace]]. In July 1653 Athanasius visited the [[Trinity-Sergius Lavra|Trinity Sergiev Monastery]].\n\nAt the request of [[Patriarch Nikon]], Athanasius wrote ''The Ordo of the Episcopal Liturgy in the East'', which underlined the Muscovian edited ''Archieratikon of the Episcopal Service'', which is used by the Russian Church to date.<ref>[http://www.liturgica.ru/bibliot/arkh_bogosl.html M. S. Zheltov. Episcopal Liturgy]</ref> Athanasius delivered the Tsar a notebook in which he stated his main reason for his visit to Moscow; that is, to arouse the Tsar unite with Moldavia and the [[Cossack Hetmanate]] for a future war with the Turks, after which the Tsar should become the new Roman Emperor, and the Moscow Patriarch \u2013 the new Ecumenical Patriarch.\n\nAthanasius is known as a trader of indulgences, which he sold in large quantities in Ukraine and Russia<ref>[[:ru:\u0413\u0438\u0434\u0443\u043b\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u041f\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447|\u0413\u0438\u0434\u0443\u043b\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u041f\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447]]. /  [http://elib.shpl.ru/ru/nodes/36762-gidulyanov-p-v-zagrobnaya-zhizn-kak-predmet-spekulyatsii-ili-indulgentsii-v-rimsko-katolicheskoy-i-greko-pravoslavnoy-tserkvi-m-ryazan-1930#mode/inspect/page/82/zoom/8 \u0417\u0430\u0433\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044c, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043c\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0443\u043b\u044f\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0434\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0440\u0438\u043c\u0441\u043a\u043e-\u043a\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e-\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0438 / \u041f. \u0412. \u0413\u0438\u0434\u0443\u043b\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432. - \u041c. ; \u0420\u044f\u0437\u0430\u043d\u044c : \u0410\u0442\u0435\u0438\u0441\u0442, 1930. - 176 \u0441. / \u0421. 163, 172]</ref>. \n\nBy December 1653 Athanasius moved to Moldavia for the Nicholas Monastery in Gala\u0163i. En route he made a visit to Bohdan Khmelnytsky. In February 1654 he stayed at the Mhar Monastery near Lubensk and died on 5 April on Thomas' Week. He was buried by the [[hegumen]] of the Transfiguration monastery, his body was in a sitting position on the throne under the [[ambon (liturgy)|ambon]].\n\n== Veneration ==\n[[File:Shrine of saint Afanasy Patellary.jpg|thumb|left|170px|Shrine of en. Athanasius at the Lubensk Monastery. [[Lithography]], 1868]]\nOn 1 February 1662, the saint's relics were [[translation (relics)|translated]] due to  the [[metropolitan of Gaza]] [[Paisios Ligaridis]], who, visiting [[Lubensk Monastery]], had a vision of Athanasius during his sleep.\nIn 1672, the Tsar requested [[podyachy]] M. Savin to investigate the wonders from the relics. In the 18th century, manuscripts of his [[hagiography]] and [[Biblical canon|canon]] were preserved at the Lubensk Monastery.\n\nIn 1818, Methodius (Pishnyachevsky), bishop of Poltava, applied the [[Most Holy Synod]] for the canonization of Athanasius, but the application was declined. However the saint's honouring and recorded wonders from his relics continued. In the 1860s, church historian [[Andrey Nikolayevich Muravyov]] created a new hagiography of Athanasius with examples of wonders at his relics.\n\nThe history of the canonization of Athanasius is vague, but the official honouring began in the Russian Church by the end of the 19th century, although [[Yevgeny Golubinsky]] through his works proved that the honouring started between 1672 and 1676 under Joseph (Nelyubovich-Tukalsky), metropolitan of Kiev (Constantinople Orthodox Church).\n\nIn 1922, the Transfiguration cathedral, including the saint's silver throne, was plundered by the [[Bolsheviks]]. The relics were moved to [[Kharkov]] in the 1930s. They were eventually preserved in the city's [[Annunciation Cathedral, Kharkiv|Annunciation Cathedral]] in 1947.\n[[File:Afanasij of Kharkov oil.JPG|thumb|95px|Oil from the relics of Patriarch Athanasius]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n# ''A. V. Ryndina, V. Shapran'' [http://www.pravenc.ru/text/76940.html Athanasius III Patellarios] // ''The Orthodox Encyclopedia.'' vol. IV \u2013 Moscow, 2002. \u2014 pp.&nbsp;20 \u2013 22.\n# [http://www.orthlib.ru/JMP/47_10/07.html St. Athanasius, Patriarch of Tsargrad, Wonderworker of Lubensk] // ''Journal of the Moscow Patriarchate''. 1947, No. 10.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://days.pravoslavie.ru/Life/life975.htm Englightener Athanasius III Patellarios, Patriarch of Tsargrad] on pravoslavie.ru\n* [http://seminaria.virtbox.ru/mon_st1.htm Englightener Athanasius, Wonderworker of Lubensk]. Short hagiography on the Poltava Missionary Spiritual Seminary of the [[Ukrainian Orthodox Church (Moscow Patriarchate)|UOC]]\n\n{{Patriarchs of Constantinople}}\n{{Bishops of Thessalonica}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Russian saints of the Eastern Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:17th-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:Ecumenical Patriarchs of Constantinople]]\n[[Category:17th-century Eastern Orthodox archbishops]]\n[[Category:17th-century people of the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Athanasius_III_of_Constantinople"}
{"title_page": "Astrakhan Tatars", "text_new": "{{further|Tatars| Tartary}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Astrakhan Tatars\n| image            = \n| population       = 60-80.000\n| region1          = {{flagcountry| Russia}}\n| pop1             = 60-80.000\n| ref1             = <ref>[http://www.perepis-2010.ru/results_of_the_census/tab5.xls Russian Census 2010: Population by ethnicity] {{webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120424113952/http://www.perepis-2010.ru/results_of_the_census/tab5.xls |date= 2012-04-24 }} {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n| region2          = \n| pop2             = \n| ref2             = \n| region3          = \n| pop3             = \n| ref3             = \n| region4          = \n| pop4             = \n| ref4             = \n| region5          = \n| pop5             = \n| ref5             = \n| languages        = [[Tatar language|Tatar]]\n| religions        = [[Sunni Islam]]\n| related          = [[Volga Tatars]]\n| footnotes        = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n'''Astrakhan Tatars''' ({{lang-tt|\u018fsterxan tatarlar\u0131, \u04d8sterhan tatarlary, Ashtarkhan tatarlar\u0131}}) are a subgroup of the [[Volga Tatar]].\n\nIn the 15th to 17th centuries the Astrakhan Tatars inhabited the [[Astrakhan Khanate]] (1459\u20131556), which was also inhabited by the [[Nogai Horde]], and the Astrakhan Tatars experienced{{huh?|date=November 2018}} a profound effect on [[Nogais]]. Since the 17th century there has been an increased interaction and ethnic mixing of the Astrakhan Tatars with [[Kazan]] Tatars.<ref>\nCompare:\n{{cite web\n|url= http://xacitarxan.narod.ru/astat.htm\n|title= History astrakhan tatars\n|quote= \n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Population==\n\nThe Astrakhan Tatars (around 80,000) are a group of Tatars, descendants of the [[Astrakhan Khanate]]'s population, who live mostly in [[Astrakhan Oblast]]. For the [[Russian Census (2010)|Russian Census in 2010]], most Astrakhan Tatars declared themselves simply as Tatars and few declared themselves as Astrakhan Tatars. A large number of Volga Tatars live in Astrakhan Oblast and differences between them have been disappearing.\n\nText from Britannica 1911:\n:The [[Astrakhan]] Tatars number about 10,000 and are, with the [[Kalmyks]], all that now remains of the once so powerful Astrakhan empire. They also are agriculturists and gardeners.\n\nWhile Astrakhan (\u00c4sterxan) Tatar is a mixed dialect, around 43,000 have assimilated to the Middle (i.e., Kazan) dialect. Their ancestors are [[Kipchaks]], [[Khazars]] and some [[Volga Bulgars]]. (Volga Bulgars had trade colonies in modern [[Astrakhan Oblast|Astrakhan]] and [[Volgograd Oblast|Volgograd]] oblasts of Russia.)\n\nThe Astrakhan Tatars also assimilated the [[Agrzhan]].<ref>Wixman, Ronald. ''The Peoples of the USSR: An Ethnographic Handbook''. (Armonk, New York: M. E. Sharpe, Inc, 1984) p. 15</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n\n=== 20th century ===\nTo 1917, the [[Astrakhan]] - one of the major centers of Tatar cultural and social life. Some Kazan Tatars settled in Astrakhan. In 1892, the functioning madrassas \"lower classes.\" The newspaper \"Azat Halyk\" (1917-1919), \"Irek\" (1917), \"Islah\" (1907), \"tartysh\" (1917-1919), \"Idel\" (1907 - 1914, renewed in 1991). News magazines \"Azat Khanum\" (1917-1918), \"Magarif\" (1909), \"Wheel\" (1907), etc. Since 1907, he has worked Tatar folk theater. In 1919, organized by Astrakhan Tatar drama school.\n\n=== Present ===\nAt present, the company operates the Astrakhan region of the Tatar national culture \"Duslyk\" and Tatar youth center \"Umid\" (founded in 1989). Parallel works \"Center of preservation and development of the Tatar culture\" at the nonprofit Partnership [http://tatar-centr.ru/ Tatar business center] (NP TDC)\n\n== Well-Known Astrakhan Tatars ==\nRenat Dasaev\n{{Empty section|date=June 2015}}\n\n== Sources ==\n\n* DM Iskhakov Astrakhan Tatars, ethnic settlement and population dynamics in the XVIII - beginning of XX century. / / Astrakhan Tatars. - Kazan, 1992. - S. 5-33.\n* The Tartars. The people of Russia. Encyclopedia. - M., 1994. - S. 320-321.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [http://xacitarxan.narod.ru/ first site Astrakhan Tatars]\n\n{{Ethnic groups of Russia}}\n\n[[Category:Tatar people]]\n[[Category:Astrakhan Khanate]]\n", "text_old": "{{further|Tatars| Tartary}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Astrakhan Tatars\n| image            = \n| population       = 60-80.000\n| region1          = {{flagcountry| Russia}}\n| pop1             = 60-80.000\n| ref1             = <ref>[http://www.perepis-2010.ru/results_of_the_census/tab5.xls Russian Census 2010: Population by ethnicity] {{webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120424113952/http://www.perepis-2010.ru/results_of_the_census/tab5.xls |date= 2012-04-24 }} {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n| region2          = \n| pop2             = \n| ref2             = \n| region3          = \n| pop3             = \n| ref3             = \n| region4          = \n| pop4             = \n| ref4             = \n| region5          = \n| pop5             = \n| ref5             = \n| languages        = [[Tatar language|Tatar]]\n| religions        = [[Sunni Islam]]\n| related          = [[Volga Tatars]]\n| footnotes        = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n'''Astrakhan Tatars''' ({{lang-tt|\u018fsterxan tatarlar\u0131, \u04d8sterhan tatarlary, Ashtarkhan tatarlar\u0131}}) are a subgroup of the [[Volga Tatar]].\n\nIn the 15th to 17th centuries the Astrakhan Tatars inhabited the [[Astrakhan Khanate]] (1459\u20131556), which was also inhabited by the [[Nogai Horde]], and the Astrakhan Tatars experienced{{huh?|date=November 2018}} a profound effect on [[Nogais]]. Since the 17th century there has been an increased interaction and ethnic mixing of the Astrakhan Tatars with [[Kazan]] Tatars<ref>\nCompare:\n{{cite web\n|url= http://xacitarxan.narod.ru/astat.htm\n|title= History astrakhan tatars\n|quote= \n}}\n</ref>.\n\n==Population==\n\nThe Astrakhan Tatars (around 80,000) are a group of Tatars, descendants of the [[Astrakhan Khanate]]'s population, who live mostly in [[Astrakhan Oblast]]. For the [[Russian Census (2010)|Russian Census in 2010]], most Astrakhan Tatars declared themselves simply as Tatars and few declared themselves as Astrakhan Tatars. A large number of Volga Tatars live in Astrakhan Oblast and differences between them have been disappearing.\n\nText from Britannica 1911:\n:The [[Astrakhan]] Tatars number about 10,000 and are, with the [[Kalmyks]], all that now remains of the once so powerful Astrakhan empire. They also are agriculturists and gardeners.\n\nWhile Astrakhan (\u00c4sterxan) Tatar is a mixed dialect, around 43,000 have assimilated to the Middle (i.e., Kazan) dialect. Their ancestors are [[Kipchaks]], [[Khazars]] and some [[Volga Bulgars]]. (Volga Bulgars had trade colonies in modern [[Astrakhan Oblast|Astrakhan]] and [[Volgograd Oblast|Volgograd]] oblasts of Russia.)\n\nThe Astrakhan Tatars also assimilated the [[Agrzhan]].<ref>Wixman, Ronald. ''The Peoples of the USSR: An Ethnographic Handbook''. (Armonk, New York: M. E. Sharpe, Inc, 1984) p. 15</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n\n=== 20th century ===\nTo 1917, the [[Astrakhan]] - one of the major centers of Tatar cultural and social life. Some Kazan Tatars settled in Astrakhan. In 1892, the functioning madrassas \"lower classes.\" The newspaper \"Azat Halyk\" (1917-1919), \"Irek\" (1917), \"Islah\" (1907), \"tartysh\" (1917-1919), \"Idel\" (1907 - 1914, renewed in 1991). News magazines \"Azat Khanum\" (1917-1918), \"Magarif\" (1909), \"Wheel\" (1907), etc. Since 1907, he has worked Tatar folk theater. In 1919, organized by Astrakhan Tatar drama school.\n\n=== Present ===\nAt present, the company operates the Astrakhan region of the Tatar national culture \"Duslyk\" and Tatar youth center \"Umid\" (founded in 1989). Parallel works \"Center of preservation and development of the Tatar culture\" at the nonprofit Partnership [http://tatar-centr.ru/ Tatar business center] (NP TDC)\n\n== Well-Known Astrakhan Tatars ==\nRenat Dasaev\n{{Empty section|date=June 2015}}\n\n== Sources ==\n\n* DM Iskhakov Astrakhan Tatars, ethnic settlement and population dynamics in the XVIII - beginning of XX century. / / Astrakhan Tatars. - Kazan, 1992. - S. 5-33.\n* The Tartars. The people of Russia. Encyclopedia. - M., 1994. - S. 320-321.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [http://xacitarxan.narod.ru/ first site Astrakhan Tatars]\n\n{{Ethnic groups of Russia}}\n\n[[Category:Tatar people]]\n[[Category:Astrakhan Khanate]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astrakhan_Tatars"}
{"title_page": "Salt (Ava Max song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 single by Ava Max}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name        = Salt\n| cover       = Ava Max Salt New Cover.jpg\n| alt         = Salt is sprinkled across a black background, forming Max's signature haircut logo. There is no text on the cover.\n| type        = single\n| artist      = [[Ava Max]]\n| album       =\n| released    = {{start date|2019|12|12|mf=y}}\n| format      =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded    = 2018\n| genre       = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[dance-pop]]<ref name=\"MTV Salt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3148895/ava-max-salt/|title=Ava Max Finally Unleashes The Fan-Favorite Anthem 'Salt'|last=Roth|first=Madeline|website=[[MTV News]]|date=December 12, 2019|access-date=December 26, 2019}}</ref>}}<!--Add source when listing genre-->\n| length      = {{duration|m=3}}\n| label       = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer      = {{hlist|[[Ava Max|Amanda Koci]]|[[Autumn Rowe]]|[[Cirkut (record producer)|Henry Walter]]|[[Madison Love]]|[[Coco Morier|Nicole Morier]]}}\n| producer    = [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]\n| chronology  = [[Ava Max]]\n| prev_title  = [[Tab\u00fa (song)|Tab\u00fa]]\n| prev_year   = 2019\n| next_title  = [[Alone, Pt. II]]\n| next_year   = 2019\n| misc        = {{Extra album cover\n| header = Alternate cover\n| type = single\n| cover = Ava Max Salt Original Cover.jpg\n| border = yes\n| caption = Original cover\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|2EfE0vhxt1o|\"Salt\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Salt'''\" is a song by American singer [[Ava Max]], released as a single on December 12, 2019 through [[Atlantic Records]], despite having already been released to [[YouTube]] and [[SoundCloud]] in July 2018.<ref name=\"Idolator\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7904225/ava-max-is-all-cried-out-feeling-fabulous-on-fierce-new-single-salt|title=Ava Max Is All Cried Out & Feeling Fabulous On Fierce New Single Salt|last=Nied|first=Mike|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|date=December 12, 2019|access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> The song has also been regarded as a \"fan favorite\".<ref name=\"MTV Salt\"/><ref name=\"Idolator\"/><ref name=\"BillboardRelease\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8546157/ava-max-salt-listen|title=Ava Max Finally Drops Fan Favorite Song 'Salt'|last=Aniftos|first=Rania|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=December 12, 2019|access-date=December 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background and composition==\n\"Salt\" was initially released on several streaming platforms in July 2018 as a promotional single, which included [[YouTube]] and [[SoundCloud]].<ref name=\"MTV Salt\"/> On December 5, 2019, Max revealed the song's release date on social media,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AvaMax/status/1202724362417139713|title=Your wish is my command \u2763\ufe0f\ud83d\ude80|via=[[Twitter]]|date=December 5, 2019|access-date=December 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206064554/https://twitter.com/AvaMax/status/1202724362417139713|archive-date=December 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> which was subsequently released on all streaming platforms on December 12, 2019.<ref name=\"BillboardRelease\"/>\n\nIt is described as a song filled with \"pumping disco beats from the seventies and eighties\", blended with Max's \"vocal inflexions\".<ref name=\"MusicTalkers\">{{cite web|url=https://musictalkers.com/latest-news/6232-ava-max-gets-down-to-disco-in-%E2%80%98salt%E2%80%99|title=Ava Max Gets Down To Disco In 'Salt'|last=Das|first=Shaoni|website=Music Talkers|date=December 19, 2019|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> A violin is heard in the introduction, while [[Wonder Woman]] and [[Marilyn Monroe]] are lyrically mentioned throughout the song.<ref name=\"MusicTalkers\"/> It is based on [[Time signature|{{Time signature|4|4}} common time]], the tempo is 128 [[Tempo|BPM]] and is played in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[D-sharp minor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tunebat.com/Info/Salt-Ava-Max/7vgv8KZBSo0TPzyIWG9yzV|title=Key & BPM for Salt by Ava Max - Tunebat|publisher=Tunebat|access-date=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nRania Aniftos of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' described the song as an \"upbeat, sassy track about having fun after a sad spell\",<ref name=\"BillboardRelease\"/> while Madeline Roth of [[MTV News]] felt that it was \"[[dance-pop]] blissfulness\".<ref name=\"MTV Salt\"/> Shaoni Das of ''Music Talkers'' stated that the song is an \"exhilarating dance number, awash in pools of glitter, glamour, and confidence\".<ref name=\"MusicTalkers\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''Digital download'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/salt-single/1490153026|title=Salt \u2013 Single|via=[[Apple Music]]|access-date=December 26, 2019}}</ref>\n#\"Salt\" \u2013 3:00\n\n*'''Digital download \u2013 acoustic'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/salt-acoustic-single/1506185126|title=Salt (Acoustic) \u2013 Single|via=[[Apple Music]]|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n#\"Salt (Acoustic)\" \u2013 3:10\n\n* '''Streaming'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/6KPJTxKFCpuzrwyJGcURqK|title=Salt|website=[[Spotify]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226032116/https://open.spotify.com/album/6KPJTxKFCpuzrwyJGcURqK|archive-date=December 26, 2019|access-date=December 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n# \"Salt\" \u2013 3:00\n# \"[[Torn (Ava Max song)|Torn]]\" \u2013 3:18\n# \"Freaking Me Out\" \u2013 3:12\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/124334771/credits|title=Salt|via=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* [[Ava Max|Amanda Ava Koci]] \u2013 vocals, songwriting\n* [[Cirkut (record producer)|Henry Walter]] \u2013 songwriting, production, mixing\n* [[Autumn Rowe]] \u2013 songwriting\n* [[Madison Love]] \u2013 songwriting\n* [[Coco Morier|Nicole Morier]] \u2013 songwriting\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|8|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|CIS|4|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|songid=98326|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Croatia ([[Croatian Radiotelevision|HRT]])<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://radio.hrt.hr/clanak/arc-100-datum-6-travnja-2020/226648/|title=Croatia ARC TOP 100|publisher=HRT|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n| 56\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=10&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 10, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| 25\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Euro Digital Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/euro-digital-song-sales|title=Euro Digital Song Sales Chart (The week of April 11, 2020)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410180005/https://www.billboard.com/charts/euro-digital-song-sales|archivedate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| 15\n|-\n{{single chart|Finland|6|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=15?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 15, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 43\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|10|songid=1928186|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}\n|-